{"title_page": "Sitnikovo, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Sitnikovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0421\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Gryazovetsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|43|N|40|17|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/gryazoveckiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u044f\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e  \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Sitnikovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Rostilovskoye Rural Settlement, [[Gryazovetsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Gryazovets]] is 15&nbsp;km, to Rostilovo is 10&nbsp;km. Obnorskaya Sloboda is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Gryazovetsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Gryazovetsky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Sitnikovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0421\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Gryazovetsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|58|43|N|40|17|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/gryazoveckiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0413\u0440\u044f\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e  \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Sitnikovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Rostilovskoye Rural Settlement, [[Gryazovetsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Gryazovets]] is 15&nbsp;km, to Rostilovo is 10&nbsp;km. Obnorskaya Sloboda is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:added navigation box and category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sitnikovo,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Jim Mattis", "text_new": "{{short description|Former US Secretary of Defense and retired US Marine Corps general}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = James Mattis official photo.jpg\n| office = 26th [[United States Secretary of Defense]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Robert O. Work]]<br />[[Patrick M. Shanahan]]\n| term_start = January 20, 2017\n| term_end = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor = [[Ash Carter]]\n| successor = [[Mark Esper]]\n| office1 = Commander of the [[United States Central Command]]\n| president1 = [[Barack Obama]]\n| term_start1 = August 11, 2010\n| term_end1 = March 22, 2013\n| predecessor1 = [[David Petraeus]]\n| successor1 = [[Lloyd Austin]]\n| office2 = Commander of the [[United States Joint Forces Command]]\n| president2 = {{ubl|[[George W. Bush]]|Barack Obama}}\n| term_start2 = November 9, 2007\n| term_end2 = August 11, 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[Lance L. Smith]]\n| successor2 = [[Raymond T. Odierno]]\n| office3 = [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]\n| deputy3 = [[Luciano Zappata]]\n| term_start3 = November 9, 2007\n| term_end3 = September 8, 2009\n| predecessor3 = Lance L. Smith\n| successor3 = [[St\u00e9phane Abrial]]\n| birth_name = James Norman Mattis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|9|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Pullman, Washington|Pullman]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = <!-- Don't insert an entry here unless you have a citation for it. -->\n| education = {{ubl|[[Central Washington University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])|[[National Defense University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])}}\n| net_worth = $5 million<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's What Each Member Of Trump's $4.5 Billion Cabinet Is Worth |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chasewithorn/2016/12/22/heres-how-much-trumps-cabinet-is-really-worth/#3b5c6faf7169 |first=Chase |last=Peterson-Withorn |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| signature = James N. Mattis Signature.svg\n| nickname = {{unbulleted list|\"Chaos\" (callsign)<ref name=Kovach>{{cite news |last1=Kovach |first1=Gretel C. |title=Just don't call him Mad Dog |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-just-dont-call-him-mad-dog-2013jan19-story.html |accessdate=November 20, 2016 |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=January 19, 2013|quote=He is a lifelong bachelor with no children, but wouldn't move into a monastery unless it was stocked with \"beer and ladies.\"}}</ref>|\"[[Warrior Monk]]\"<ref name=Kovach /><ref name=ArmedForceJournal>{{cite web |url=http://www.armedforcesjournal.com/the-corps-should-look-to-its-small-wars-past/ |accessdate=July 29, 2014 |title=The Corps should look to its small-wars past |authorlink=Max Boot |last=Boot |first=Max |work=[[Armed Forces Journal]] |date=March 2006}}</ref>|\"Mad Dog\"<ref name=ArmedForceJournal />}}\n| allegiance = United States\n| branch = [[United States Marine Corps]]\n| serviceyears = 1969\u20132013\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USMCO10}} [[General (United States)|General]]\n| commands = {{unbulleted list|[[United States Central Command]]|[[United States Joint Forces Command]]|[[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]|[[I Marine Expeditionary Force]]|[[United States Marine Forces Central Command]]|[[Marine Corps Combat Development Command]]|[[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]]|[[1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade]]|[[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|7th Marine Regiment]]|[[1st Battalion 7th Marines|1st Battalion, 7th Marines]]}}\n| battles = {{unbulleted list|[[Gulf War]]|[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]]|[[Iraq War]]|{{*}}[[2003 invasion of Iraq|Invasion of Iraq]]|{{*}}[[First Battle of Fallujah]]|{{*}}[[Second Battle of Fallujah]]}}\n| mawards = {{unbulleted list|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)|[[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]|[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]|[[Legion of Merit]]|[[Bronze Star Medal]] (with [[\"V\" device|Valor]])|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] (3)}}\n}}\n'''James Norman<!-- \"Mad Dog\" is already a listed nickname in the infobox. Don't add it here. --> Mattis''' (born September 8, 1950) is a retired United States Marine general and former government official who served as the 26th [[United States Secretary of Defense]] from January 2017 through January 2019. A retired [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|general]], Mattis served in the [[Persian Gulf War]], the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]], and the [[Iraq War]].\n\nMattis was commissioned in the Marine Corps through the [[Naval Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] after graduating from [[Central Washington University]]. A career Marine, he gained a reputation among his peers for \"intellectualism\", and eventually advanced to the rank of general. From 2007 to 2010 he commanded the [[United States Joint Forces Command]] and concurrently served as [[NATO]]'s [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]. He was Commander of [[United States Central Command]] from 2010 to 2013 with Admiral Bob Harward serving as his Deputy Commander. After retiring from the military, he served in several private sector roles, including as a board member of [[Theranos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/16/17124288/mattis-theranos-board-trump|title=James Mattis is linked to a massive corporate fraud and nobody wants to talk about it|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=March 16, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMattis was nominated as Secretary of Defense by President-elect [[Donald Trump]], and confirmed by the Senate on January 20, 2017. As Secretary of Defense, Mattis affirmed the United States' commitment to defending longtime ally [[South Korea]] in the wake of the [[2017\u201318 North Korea crisis|2017 North Korea crisis]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/world/asia/james-mattis-us-korea-thaad.html |title=James Mattis, in South Korea, Tries to Reassure an Ally |newspaper=The New York Times |date=February 2, 2017\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108153812/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/world/asia/james-mattis-us-korea-thaad.html?_r=0 |archive-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/warns-north-korea-nuclear-attack-170203034440571.html |title=US warns North Korea against nuclear attack |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204092355/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/warns-north-korea-nuclear-attack-170203034440571.html |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |work=Al Jazeera |date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> An opponent of proposed collaboration with [[China]] and [[Russia]],<ref name=\"baldor\">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mattis-us-ready-collaborate-militarily-russia-45531272|title=Mattis: US not ready to collaborate militarily with Russia |last=Baldor |first=Lolita |date=February 16, 2017 |publisher=ABC News |agency=Associated Press|accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> Mattis stressed what he saw as their \"threat to the American-led world order\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/amp/2386071002|title=Donald Trump disputes departing Defense Secretary Jim Mattis over Russia, China|last=Jackson|first=David|date=December 21, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Press TV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/01/13/506051/James-Mattis-Defense-Department-Donald-Trump-Vladimir-Putin |title=US needs to be ready to confront Russia: Trump's Pentagon pick |publisher= Press TV |date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Mattis occasionally voiced his disagreement with certain Trump administration policies such as the withdrawal from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran nuclear deal]],<ref name=\"Washington Examiner\">{{cite news |last1=McIntyre |first1=Jamie |title=Mattis: Iran is the biggest threat to Mideast peace |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mattis-iran-is-the-biggest-threat-to-mideast-peace/article/2589267 |accessdate=December 2, 2016 |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> withdrawals of troops from Syria and Afghanistan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/20/623246756/defense-secretary-mattis-to-retire-in-february-trump-says|title=Defense Secretary Mattis Resigns Amid Syria And Afghanistan Tension|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> and budget cuts hampering the ability to [[climate security|monitor the impacts of climate change]].<ref name=\"Union of Concerned Scientists\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.ucsusa.org/shana-udvardy/secretary-of-defense-james-mattis-the-lone-climate-change-soldier-in-this-administrations-cabinet |title=Secretary of Defense James Mattis: The Lone Climate Change Soldier in this Administration's Cabinet |year=2017 |publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/weather/2018/01/31/climate-change-extreme-weather-military-defense-department-trump-global-warming-wildfires-droughts/1079278001/ |title=Climate change, extreme weather already threaten 50% of U.S. military sites |work=USA Today |date= January 31, 2018}}</ref> On December 20, 2018, after failing to convince Trump to reconsider his decision to withdraw all American troops from Syria, Mattis announced his resignation effective February 28, 2019. Trump, angered by the language of the resignation letter, accelerated the departure date to January 1, stating he had essentially fired him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/02/us/politics/trump-mattis-defense-secretary-generals.html|title=Trump Says Mattis Resignation Was \u2018Essentially\u2019 a Firing, Escalating His New Front Against Military Critics|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=2019-01-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMattis was born on September 8, 1950, in [[Pullman, Washington]].<ref name=SenateNom>{{cite web|title=Nominations before the Senate Armed Services Committee, Second Session, 111th Congress|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-111shrg65070/pdf/CHRG-111shrg65070.pdf|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> He is the son of Lucille (Proulx) Mattis (1922\u20132019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lucille Mattis Obituary|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tricityherald/obituary.aspx?pid=193576447|work =The Tri-City Herald|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref> and John West Mattis (1915\u20131988),<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About James Mattis|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-01-13/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-james-mattis|accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=James Mattis Fast Facts|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/26/us/James-mattis-fast-facts/|publisher=CNN Library|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> a [[United States Merchant Marine|merchant mariner]]. His mother immigrated to the United States from Canada as an infant and had worked in [[Military Intelligence Corps (United States Army)|Army Intelligence]] in [[South Africa]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Reflections with General James Mattis \u2013 Conversations with History|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HOc38ZwEO8s|publisher=University Of California Television|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Mattis's father moved to [[Richland, Washington]], to work at a [[Hanford Site|plant]] supplying [[fissile material]] to the [[Manhattan Project]].<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /> Mattis was raised in a bookish household that did not own a television.<ref name=\"NYBIO\">{{cite news |work=[[The New Yorker]] |title=James Mattis, a Warrior in Washington |date=May 29, 2017 |access-date=May 22, 2017 |url=https://newyorker.com/magazine/2017/05/29/james-mattis-a-warrior-in-washington}}</ref> He graduated from [[Richland High School (Washington)|Richland High School]] in 1968.<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kraemer|first1=Kristin M.|title=Gen. Mattis, Trump's possible defense chief, fulfills Benton County jury duty|url=http://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/article116590898.html|work=Tri-City Herald|date=November 22, 2016}}</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[history]] from [[Central Washington University]] in 1971<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/James-Mattis |title=James Mattis |encyclopedia=Britannica |first=Michael |last=Ray |date=December 2, 2016 |accessdate=December 6, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220233204/https://www.britannica.com/biography/James-Mattis |archivedate=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Baldor>{{cite news|last1=Baldor|first1=Lolita C.|title=Trump to nominate retired Gen. James Mattis to lead Pentagon|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/whitehouse/trump-to-nominate-retired-gen-james-mattis-to-lead-pentagon/2016/12/01/fc8d55a8-b831-11e6-939c-91749443c5e5_story.html|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfcom.mil/|title=Official website|work=United States Joint Forces Command|access-date=September 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010202023400/http://www.jfcom.mil/|archive-date=February 2, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> and a [[Master of Arts]] in international security affairs from the [[National War College]] of [[National Defense University]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Historical Office\">{{cite web|url=http://history.defense.gov/Multimedia/Biographies/Article-View/Article/1059855/james-n-mattis/|title=James N. Mattis \u2013 Donald Trump Administration|work=Office of the Secretary of Defense \u2013 Historical Office}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\nMattis enlisted in the [[Marine Corps]] Reserve in 1969.<ref>{{cite AV media | people = Mattis, James | date = September 25, 2013 | title = General James Mattis, \"In the Midst of the Storm: A US Commander's View of the Changing Middle East\" | url =  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vzl8hZWzVpI | access-date = June 2, 2015 | time = 80:10 | publisher = [[Dartmouth College]]}}</ref> He was commissioned a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] on January 1, 1972.<ref name=Reynolds>{{cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Nicholas E.|authorlink=|title=Basrah, Baghdad and Beyond|url=https://archive.org/details/basrahbaghdadbey00reyn/page/4|accessdate=February 20, 2013|year=2005|publisher=|location=|isbn=978-1-59114-717-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/basrahbaghdadbey00reyn/page/4 4\u20135]}}</ref> During his service years, Mattis was considered an \"intellectual\" among the upper ranks.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Ricks|first1=Thomas E.|title=Fiasco|journal=Armed Forces Journal|date=August 1, 2006|url=http://www.armedforcesjournal.com/fiasco/|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Robert H. Scales]], a retired [[United States Army]] [[Major General (United States)|major general]], called him \"one of the most urbane and polished men I have known.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2017/08/james-mattis-no-better-friend-no-worse-enemy/|title=James Mattis: No Better Friend, No Worse Enemy|last=PROSER|first=JIM|date=August 15, 2017|website=Nationalreview|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\nAs a lieutenant, Mattis was assigned as a rifle and weapons [[platoon]] commander in the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]]. As a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], he was assigned as the [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]]'s [[Battalion]] Officer, commanded rifle and weapons companies in the [[1st Marine Regiment (United States)|1st Marine Regiment]], then served at [[Marine Corps Recruiting Command#12th Marine Corps District|Recruiting Station]] [[Portland, Oregon]], as a [[Major (United States)|major]].<ref name=hall />\n\nMattis is a graduate of the U.S. Marine Corps Amphibious Warfare School, [[U.S. Marine Corps Command and Staff College]], and the [[National War College]]. He is noted for his interest in the study of [[military history]] and [[world history]],<ref name=Ricks /><ref name=\"A Marine General at War\" /> with a personal library that once included over 7,000 volumes,<ref name=Kovach /> and a penchant for publishing required reading lists for Marines under his command.<ref name=\"LtGen James Mattis' Reading List\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Small Wars Journal]]|title=LtGen James Mattis' Reading List|url=http://smallwarsjournal.com/blog/ltgen-james-mattis-reading-list|date=June 5, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Ricks, p. 317\">{{cite book| last=Ricks |title=Fiasco: The American Military Adventure in Iraq |page=317}}</ref> He required his Marines to be well-read in the culture and history of regions where they were deployed, and had his Marines deploying to Iraq undergo \"cultural sensitivity training\".<ref name=\"A Marine General at War\" />\n\n=== Persian Gulf War ===\nUpon promotion to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]], Mattis commanded [[1st Battalion, 7th Marines]], one of [[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|Task Force Ripper]]'s assault battalions during the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"Lowry\">{{cite news|last1=Lowry|first1=Richard|title=Op-ed: General James N. Mattis \u2013 A Marine for the History Books|url=http://americanmilitarynews.com/2016/12/op-ed-general-james-n-mattis-a-marine-for-the-history-books/|accessdate=March 10, 2017|work=[[American Military News]]|date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== War in Afghanistan ===\n{{further|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\nAs a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]], Mattis commanded the [[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|7th Marine Regiment]]. He led the [[1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] as its commanding officer upon promotion to brigadier general.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Mark|title=Mattis to assume command of I MEF|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-mattis-to-assume-command-of-i-mef-2006jun02-story.html|accessdate=May 19, 2017|newspaper=San Diego Union-Tribune|date=June 2, 2006}}</ref> It was as a regimental commander that he earned his nickname and call sign, \"CHAOS\", an acronym for \"Colonel Has An Outstanding Solution\", which was initially somewhat tongue-in-cheek.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=McKenzie|title=The origin of Mattis' call sign, 'Chaos'|url=https://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/your-marine-corps/2017/09/21/mattis-explains-the-origin-of-the-call-sign-chaos/|accessdate=October 20, 2017|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|date=September 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the initial planning for the War in Afghanistan, Mattis led [[Task Force 58]] in operations in the southern part of the country beginning in November 2001,<ref>{{cite news |first=Gal Perl|last=Finkel |url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/General-Mattis-A-warrior-diplomat-475187 |title=General Mattis: A warrior diplomat |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220162731/http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/General-Mattis-A-warrior-diplomat-475187 |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> becoming the first Marine Corps officer to command a Naval Task Force in combat.<ref name=Reynolds /> According to Mattis, his objective upon arriving in Afghanistan was \"make sure that the enemy didn't feel like they had any safe haven, to destroy their sense of security in southern Afghanistan, to isolate [[Kandahar]] from its lines of communication, and to move against Kandahar.\"<ref name=\"BARZILAI2014\">{{cite book|first=Yaniv |last=Barzilai |title=102 Days of War: How Osama bin Laden, al Qaeda & the Taliban Survived 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsvQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=January 31, 2014|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|isbn=978-1-61234-534-5|pages=45ff.}}</ref> In December 2001 an airstrike carried out by a [[B-52]] bomber inadvertently targeted a position held by U.S. [[special operations]] troops and Afghan militiamen in [[Urozgan Province]]. Numerous men were wounded in the incident, but Mattis repeatedly refused to dispatch helicopters from the nearby [[Camp Rhino]] to recover them, citing operational safety concerns. Instead an Air Force helicopter flew from [[Uzbekistan]] to ferry the men to the [[U.S. Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] base where helicopters sat readily available but unauthorized to fly. Captain [[Jason Amerine]] blamed the delay caused by Mattis's refusal to order a rescue operation for the deaths of several men. Amerine wrote, \"Every element in Afghanistan tried to help us except the closest friendly unit, commanded by Mattis,\" though he also wrote that \"none of that was assessed properly because the [5th Special Forces Group] chose not to call for a formal investigation\".<ref name=\"Tritten 2016\">{{cite web |last=Tritten |first=Travis J. |title=Retired Green Beret says Mattis left 'my men to die' in Afghanistan |website=Stars and Stripes |date=December 2, 2016 |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/retired-green-beret-says-mattis-left-my-men-to-die-in-afghanistan-1.442367 |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Vladimirov 2016\">{{cite web |last=Vladimirov |first=Nikita |title=Former Special Forces officer: Mattis 'betrayed his duty to us' |work=The Hill |date=December 2, 2016 |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/308527-former-special-forces-officer-blasts-trump-defense-secretary |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> This episode was used against Mattis when he was nominated for Defense Secretary in 2016.<ref name=\"Meek Ferran 2016\">{{cite web |last=Meek |first=James Gordon |last2=Ferran |first2=Lee |title=Men Left 'to Die': Gen. James Mattis' Controversial Wartime Decision |publisher=ABC News |date=December 6, 2016 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/men-left-die-gen-james-mattis-controversial-wartime/story?id=44018222 |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving in Afghanistan as a [[brigadier general]], Mattis was known{{by whom|date=January 2019}} as an officer who engaged his men with \"real leadership.\"{{clarify|date=January 2019}} He also was quoted as saying \"be polite, be courteous, and have a plan to kill everyone you meet.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/07/16-most-hair-raising-general-mattis-quotes/340553/|title=16 Most Hair-Raising General Mattis Quotes|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=July 9, 2010|work=The Atlantic|access-date=September 5, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> A young Marine officer, [[Nathaniel Fick]], said he witnessed Mattis in a [[Defensive fighting position|fighting hole]] talking with a sergeant and lance corporal: \"No one would have questioned Mattis if he'd slept eight hours each night in a private room, to be woken each morning by an aide who ironed his uniforms and heated his [[Meal, Ready-to-Eat|MREs]]. But there he was, in the middle of a freezing night, out on the lines with his Marines.\"<ref name=RicksG>{{cite book|author-link=Thomas E. Ricks (journalist) |first=Thomas E.|last= Ricks|title=The Generals: American Military Command from World War II to Today|date=2012|page=405|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-59420-404-3}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq War ===\n[[File:Genmattisltr.jpg|thumb|200px|Letter written by Mattis on the eve of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], addressed to members of the 1st Marine Division]]\nAs a [[Major general (United States)|major general]], Mattis commanded the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=Ricks>{{cite book|title=[[Fiasco (book)|Fiasco: The American Military Adventure in Iraq]]|author-link=Thomas E. Ricks (journalist) |first=Thomas E.|last= Ricks|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York|year=2006|page=313}}</ref> Mattis played key roles in combat operations in [[Fallujah]], including negotiation with the insurgent command inside the city during [[First Battle of Fallujah|Operation Vigilant Resolve]] in April 2004, as well as participation in planning of the subsequent [[Second Battle of Fallujah|Operation Phantom Fury]] in November.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szoldra|first1=Paul|title=19 unforgettable quotes from legendary Marine Gen. James 'Mad Dog' Mattis|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/general-mattiss-best-quotes-2016-11/#i-dont-lose-any-sleep-at-night-over-the-potential-for-failure-i-cannot-even-spell-the-word-7|accessdate=May 19, 2017|work=Business Insider|date=December 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2004 Mattis ordered the 3&nbsp;a.m. bombing of what he alleged was a suspected enemy [[safe house]] near the Syrian border, but was in fact [[Mukaradeeb_wedding_party_massacre|a wedding party]] and resulted in the deaths of 42 civilians, including 11 women and 14 children. Mattis said it had taken him 30 seconds to decide whether to bomb the location. Describing the wedding as implausible, he said, \"How many people go to the middle of the desert to hold a wedding {{Convert|80|mi|abbr=out}} from the nearest civilization? These were more than two dozen military-age males. Let's not be naive.\"<ref>{{Cite book|first=Bing|last=West|year=2008|title=The Strongest Tribe: War, Politics, and the Endgame in Iraq|location=New York, NY|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=978-1-4000-6701-5|p=[https://archive.org/details/strongesttribewa00west/page/245 245]|url=https://archive.org/details/strongesttribewa00west/page/245}}</ref> The occurrence of a wedding was disputed by military officials, but the [[Associated Press]] obtained video footage showing a wedding party and a video the next day showed musical instruments and party decoration among the remains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2004/05/24/iraq-wedding-party-video-backs-survivors-claims.html|title=Iraq Wedding-Party Video Backs Survivors' Claims|date=May 24, 2004|newspaper=Fox News|access-date=February 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204165706/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2004/05/24/iraq-wedding-party-video-backs-survivors-claims.html|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked by the press about footage on Arabic television of a child's body being lowered into a grave, he replied: \"I have not seen the pictures but bad things happen in wars. I don't have to apologise for the conduct of my men.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/may/21/iraq.rorymccarthy|title='US soldiers started to shoot us, one by one'|date=20 May 2004|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a Department of Defense survey that showed only 55% of U.S. soldiers and 40% of Marines would report a colleague for abusing civilians, Mattis told Marines in May 2007 that \"whenever you show anger or disgust toward civilians, it's a victory for [[al-Qaeda]] and other insurgents.\" Believing that a need for restraint in war is key to defeating an insurgency, he added: \"every time you wave at an Iraqi civilian, al-Qaeda rolls over in its grave.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=General Urges Marines To Add A Friendly Wave To Their Arsenal|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/17/world/fg-force17|last=Perry|first=Tony|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 17, 2007|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMattis popularized the 1st Marine Division's motto \"no better friend, no worse enemy\", a paraphrase of the epitaph the [[Roman dictator]] [[Sulla|Lucius Cornelius Sulla]] wrote for himself,<ref name=Durant>{{cite book |last=Durant |first=Will |authorlink=Will Durant|title=Heroes of History: A Brief History of Civilization from Ancient Times to the Dawn of the Modern Age |url=https://archive.org/details/heroesofhistoryb00dura |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |date=2001 |page=[https://archive.org/details/heroesofhistoryb00dura/page/131 131] |isbn=0-7432-2910-X}}</ref> in his open letter to all men within the division for their return to Iraq. This phrase later became widely publicized during the investigation into the conduct of Lieutenant [[Ilario Pantano]], a platoon commander serving under Mattis.<ref name=StarNewsOnline051228>{{cite news|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20051228/NEWS/51227016&SearchID=73247366207350|title=Top 10 Stories of 2005: Pantano, roads, Olchowski are 10\u20137|date=December 28, 2005|work=Star News Online|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=Time050228>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1032357-1,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|title=Did He Go Too Far?|date=February 28, 2005|author=Quinn-Judge, Paul|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=Msnbc060426>{{cite news|date=April 26, 2005|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7250029|title=Marine charged with murders of Iraqis: Lieutenant claims self-defense in shooting of detainees|publisher=[[NBC News]]|author=Phillips, Stone|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=StarsAndStripes0511116>{{cite news|url=http://stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=33048|title=Marine acquitted in Iraqi shootings will publish a book|author=Jeff Schogol|work=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|date=November 16, 2005|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=NorthCountyTimes060701>{{cite news|url=http://www.nctimes.com/articles/2006/07/02/news/top_stories/22_22_057_1_06.txt|title=Pantano case has parallels to Hamdania incident|author=Walker, Mark|date=July 1, 2006|work=[[North County Times]]|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAs his division prepared to ship out, Mattis called in \"experts on the Middle East\" for \"cultural sensitivity training\". He constantly toured the battlefield to tell stories of Marines who were able to show \"discretion in moments of high pressure\". As an apparent example, he encouraged his Marines to grow moustaches to look more like the people they were working with.<ref name=\"A Marine General at War\">{{cite news|url-status=live |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/risk/2010/04/a_marine_general_at_war.html |title=A Marine General at War |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111121158/http://www.slate.com/articles/life/risk/2010/04/a_marine_general_at_war.html |archive-date=January 11, 2017 |first=John |last=Dickerson |work=Slate |date=April 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe also was noted for a willingness to remove senior leaders under his command at a time when the U.S. military seemed unable or unwilling to relieve underperforming or incompetent officers. During the division's push to Baghdad, Mattis relieved Colonel Joe D. Dowdy, commander of [[1st Marine Regiment (United States)|Regimental Combat Team-1]]. It was such a rare occurrence in the modern military that it made the front page of newspapers. Despite this, Mattis declined to comment on the matter publicly other than to say that the practice of officer relief remains alive, or at least \"we are doing it in the Marines.\"<ref name=RicksG /> Later interviews of Dowdy's officers and men revealed that \"the colonel was doomed partly by an age-old wartime tension: Men versus mission\u2014in which he favored his men\", while Mattis insisted on execution of the mission to seize Baghdad swiftly.<ref name=WSJ_Cooper>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108111980285073875|title=How a Marine Lost His Command In Race to Baghdad|author=Cooper, Christopher|date=April 5, 2004|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Combat Development Command ===\nAfter being promoted to [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]], Mattis took command of [[Marine Corps Combat Development Command]]. On February 1, 2005, speaking at a forum in [[San Diego]], he said \"You go into Afghanistan, you got guys who slap women around for five years because they didn't wear a veil. You know, guys like that ain't got no manhood left anyway. So it's a hell of a lot of fun to shoot them. Actually, it's a lot of fun to fight. You know, it's a hell of a hoot. It's fun to shoot some people. I'll be right upfront with you, I like brawling.\" Mattis's remarks sparked controversy; General [[Michael Hagee]], [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]], issued a statement suggesting Mattis should have chosen his words more carefully but would not be disciplined.<ref name=AmericanSpectator>{{cite web |url=https://spectator.org/48978_breaking-warrior-code/ |title=Breaking the Warrior Code |author= Guardiano, John R. |work=[[The American Spectator]] |date=February 11, 2005 |accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== U.S. Joint Forces Command ===\n[[File:From left, Vice President Joe Biden, Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Navy Adm. Mike Mullen and U.S. Marine Corps Gen. Gen. James Mattis, the commander of U.S. Central 100901-N-TT977-147.jpg|thumb|left|Vice President [[Joe Biden]], Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]], Admiral [[Mike Mullen]] and General Mattis in Baghdad, Iraq]]\n\n[[The Pentagon]] announced on May 31, 2006, that Mattis had been chosen to take command of the [[I Marine Expeditionary Force]], based out of [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton]].<ref name = MCTimes>{{cite news|first=Christian |last=Lowe|title=Popular commander to lead I MEF|work=[[Marine Corps Times]]|page=24|date=June 12, 2006}}</ref> On September 11, 2007, Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] announced that President [[George W. Bush]] had nominated Mattis for appointment to the rank of general to command [[United States Joint Forces Command|U.S. Joint Forces Command]] in [[Norfolk, Virginia]]. NATO agreed to appoint Mattis as [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]. On September 28, 2007, the [[United States Senate]] confirmed Mattis's nomination, and he relinquished command of the I MEF on November 5, 2007, to Lieutenant General Samuel Helland.<ref name=\"hall\">{{cite web|title=Gen James N. Mattis|url=http://www.militaryhallofhonor.com/honoree-record.php?id=405|publisher=Military Hall of Honor|accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMattis was promoted to four-star general and took control of JFCOM/[[Allied Command Transformation|SACT]] on November 9, 2007. He transferred the job of SACT to General [[St\u00e9phane Abrial]] of France on September 9, 2009, but continued in command of JFCOM.<ref name=\"NATOawards\" />\n\n=== U.S. Central Command ===\nIn early 2010 Mattis was reported to be on the list of generals being considered to replace [[James T. Conway]] as the Commandant of the U.S. Marine Corps.<ref name=\"CMC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/06/ap_CMC_062110/|title=Gates announces nomination of Amos for CMC|last=Gearan|first=Anne|date=June 22, 2010|agency=Associated Press|work=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322203931/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/06/ap_CMC_062110/ |archivedate=March 22, 2012}}</ref> In July he was recommended by [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert Gates]] for nomination to replace [[David Petraeus]] as commander of [[United States Central Command]] (CENTCOM),<ref name=SenateNom /><ref name=\"MCT CENTCOM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/military_mattis_centcom_070810w/|title=Pentagon picks Mattis to take over CENTCOM|last=Cavallaro|first=Gina|date=July 8, 2010|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 8, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712031949/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/military_mattis_centcom_070810w/|archivedate=July 12, 2010}}</ref> and formally nominated by President Obama on July 21.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/marine_mattis_centcom_072110w/|title=Obama backs Mattis nomination for CENTCOM|date=July 22, 2010|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 23, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117234339/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/marine_mattis_centcom_072110w/|archivedate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Mattis had planned to retire before the appointment.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2012/04/centcom-commander-general-mad-dog-mattis-set-to-retire/|title=CENTCOM Commander \u2018Mad Dog\u2019 General James Mattis Set To Retire|first=Dark|last=Laughter|date=April 27, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis confirmation by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] marked the first time Marines had held billets as commander and deputy commander of a [[unified combatant command]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fayobserver.com/articles/2010/08/06/1019648|title=Petraeus' replacement at Central Command confirmed|date=August 6, 2010|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Fayetteville Observer]]|accessdate=August 6, 2010}}</ref> He took command at a ceremony at [[MacDill Air Force Base]] on August 11.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2010/08/11/mattis-takes-central-command-vows-work-mideast-allies-afghanistan-iraq/|title=Mattis takes over Central Command, vows to work with Mideast allies in Afghanistan, Iraq|date=August 11, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/article1114800.ece|title=Mattis takes over as CentCom chief|last=Mitchell|first=Robbyn|date=August 12, 2010|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|page=1|accessdate=August 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012171654/http://www.tampabay.com/news/article1114800.ece|archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centcom.mil/news/mattis-assumes-command-of-centcom|title=Mattis assumes command of CENTCOM|date=August 11, 2010|publisher=U.S. Central Command|accessdate=August 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs head of Central Command, Mattis oversaw the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan and was responsible for a region that includes [[Syria]], Iran, and Yemen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/04/11/syria-iran-mattis-central-command-chief-interview/2069935/|title=Mattis interview: Syria would fall without Iran's help|date=April 12, 2013|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=September 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011204715/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/04/11/syria-iran-mattis-central-command-chief-interview/2069935/|archive-date=October 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He lobbied the Obama administration for a more aggressive response to Iran, including more covert operations and disruption of Iranian arms shipments to Syria and [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Why the chaos in Yemen could force Obama to take a harder line with Iran |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-sectarian-chaos-spreads-obamas-middle-east-policy-buckles/2015/03/28/f8cc8f56-d570-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html |work=Washington Post |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=March 28, 2015|first1=Greg |last1= Jaffe |first2=Missy |last2=Ryan}}</ref> According to [[Leon Panetta]], the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] did not place much trust in Mattis because he was perceived as too eager for a military confrontation with [[Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Panetta|first=Leon|title=Worthy Fights: A Memoir of Leadership in War and Peace|pp=Kindle Locations 6368\u20136370|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|edition=Kindle}}</ref> Panetta later said Mattis lacked \"the maturity to look at all of the options that a president should look at in order to make the right decisions\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/as-a-general-mattis-urged-action-against-iran-as-a-defense-secretary-he-may-be-a-voice-of-caution/2017/01/08/5a196ade-d391-11e6-a783-cd3fa950f2fd_story.html |work=Washington Post |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |title=As a general, Mattis urged action against Iran. As a defense secretary, he may be a voice of caution.|date=January 8, 2017 |first1=Greg |last1=Jaffe |first2=Adam |last2=Entous}}</ref>\n\nMattis announced his retirement from the Marine Corps in April 2012, effective in a matter of months.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Eight months later, the Defense Department nominated General [[Lloyd Austin]] to succeed Mattis, who retired in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/austin-will-be-nominated-to-lead-us-central-command-1.199642|title=Austin will be nominated to lead US Central Command|website=Stars and Stripes|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=FWA /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/About/Biographies/Biography-View/Article/1055835/james-mattis|title=James Mattis|publisher=United States Department of Defense|quote=Following his retirement from the U.S. Marine Corps in 2013, Secretary Mattis served as the Davies Family Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, specializing in the study of leadership, national security, strategy, innovation, and the effective use of military force.}}</ref>\n\n== Civilian career ==\n[[File:James Mattis official Transition portrait.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Mattis in 2016]]\nAfter retiring from the military, Mattis worked for FWA Consultants and served as a member of the [[General Dynamics]] Board of Directors.<ref name=FWA>{{cite web|url=http://fwaconsultants.homestead.com/MattisBio.html|title=About General James Mattis|publisher=FWA Consultants|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> Between 2013 and 2017, while on the board of [[General Dynamics]], Mattis made more than $900,000 in compensation, including company stock.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/political-capital/donald-trump-pentagon-pick-mattis-made-nearly-1000000-board-defense-contractor|title=Donald Trump Pentagon Pick Mattis Made Nearly $1,000,000 On Board Of Defense Contractor|last=Asher-Schapiro|first=Avi|date=2016-12-02|website=International Business Times|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In August 2013, he was appointed an Annenberg Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the [[Hoover Institution]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoover.org/profiles/james-mattis|title=General James Mattis, Annenberg Distinguished Visiting Fellow|publisher=Hoover Institute|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> and in 2016 he was named the Davies Family Distinguished Visiting Fellow.<ref>{{cite web|title=General James Mattis|url=http://www.hoover.org/profiles/james-mattis|publisher=Hoover Institution|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Mattis joined the [[advisory board]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mattis|first1=James|title=Why I'm Joining Spirit of America|url=https://spiritofamerica.org/blog/im-joining-spirit-america|publisher=Spirit of America|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> of [[Spirit of America (charity)|Spirit of America]], a [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)(3) nonprofit organization]] that provides assistance to support the safety and success of American service personnel and the local people they seek to help.\n\nHe is co-editor of the book ''Warriors & Citizens: American Views of Our Military'', published in August 2016.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Mattis|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Schake|editor2-first=Kori|editor2link=Kori Schake|title=Warriors and Citizens: American Views of Our Military|date=August 2016|publisher=[[Hoover Institution]]|location=Stanford, California|isbn=978-0-8179-1934-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1gpmDAAAQBAJ|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2013 to January 2017, Mattis was a board member of [[Theranos]], a [[Health technology in the United States|health technology]] company that claimed to have devised revolutionary [[blood test]]s using very small amounts of blood.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Carreyrou|title=Bad Blood: Secrets and Lies in a Silicon Valley Startup|date=May 21, 2018|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-5247-3166-3}}{{page needed|date=December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Levine|first1=Matt|title=The Blood Unicorn Theranos Was Just a Fairy Tale|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-03-14/theranos-misled-investors-and-consumers-who-used-its-blood-test|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=Bloomberg View|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Christopher|title=Trump Defense Nominee James Mattis Resigns From Theranos Board|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defense-nominee-james-mattis-resigns-from-theranos-board-1483649696|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/06/12/theranos-board-directors/|title=A singular board at Theranos|date=June 12, 2014|work=Fortune|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> Previously, in mid-2012, a Department of Defense official evaluating Theranos's blood-testing technology for the military initiated a formal inquiry with the [[Food and Drug Administration]] about the company's intent to distribute its tests without FDA clearance. In August 2012 Theranos CEO [[Elizabeth Holmes]] asked Mattis, who had expressed interest in testing Theranos's technology in combat areas, to help. Within hours, Mattis forwarded his email exchange with Holmes to military officials, asking \"how do we overcome this new obstacle\". In July 2013 the Department of Defense gave Mattis permission to join Theranos's board provided he did not represent Theranos with regard to the blood-testing device and its potential acquisition by the Departments of the Navy or Defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/02/internal-emails-reveal-concerns-about-theranoss-fda-compliance-date-back-years/ |title=E-mails reveal concerns about Theranos's FDA compliance date back years|date=December 2, 2015|first =Carolyn Y.|last= Johnson|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Mattis's book ''Call Sign Chaos: Learning to Lead'' was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/30/books/review/call-sign-chaos-jim-mattis-and-bing-west.html|title=Jim Mattis Tells His Life Story|first=Risa|last=Brooks|date=August 30, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> It is an autobiography as well as an argument in favor of an [[Internationalism (politics)|internationalist]] foreign policy.<ref>Goldberg, Jeffrey.  [https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/10/james-mattis-trump/596665/ \"Why Did James Mattis Resign ....\"] ''The Atlantic''.  October 2019.  29 August 2019.</ref> On August 7, 2019, Mattis was re-elected to the board of [[General Dynamics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gd.com/Articles/2019/08/07/general-dynamics-elects-jim-mattis-to-board-of-directors|title=General Dynamics Elects Jim Mattis to Board of Directors|website=www.gd.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\n== Secretary of Defense (2017\u20132019) ==\n\n=== Nomination and confirmation ===\n[[File:President Donald J. Trump departs from the Pentagon alongside Secretary of Defense James Mattis on January 27, 2017, in Washington, D.C. (32181624010).jpg|thumb|right|Mattis with President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] and Vice President [[Mike Pence|Pence]]]]\nThen-President-elect [[Donald Trump]] met with Mattis for a little over one hour in [[Bedminster, New Jersey]], on November 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/19/politics/donald-trump-james-mattis-defense-secretary/index.html|title=Trump: 'Mad Dog' Mattis is a 'very impressive' candidate for defense secretary|date=November 20, 2016|author=Phil Mattingly|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> He later wrote on [[Twitter]], \"General James 'Mad Dog' Mattis, who is being considered for Secretary of Defense, was very impressive yesterday. A true General's General!\"<ref>{{cite tweet  |user=realDonaldTrump |number=800332639844659201|title=General James \"Mad Dog\" Mattis, who is being considered for Secretary of Defense, was very impressive yesterday. A true General's General! |date=November 11, 2016|first=Donald J.|last=Trump |accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> On December 1, 2016, Trump announced at a rally in Cincinnati that he would nominate Mattis for [[United States Secretary of Defense]].<ref name=wp20161201>{{cite news|last=Lamothe |first=Dan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-has-chosen-retired-marine-gen-james-mattis-for-secretary-of-defense/2016/12/01/6c6b3b74-aff9-11e6-be1c-8cec35b1ad25_story.html |title=Trump has chosen retired Marine Gen. James Mattis for secretary of defense |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs Mattis retired from the military in 2013, his nomination required a waiver of the [[National Security Act of 1947]], which requires a seven-year waiting period before retired military personnel can assume the role of Secretary of Defense.<ref name=wp20161201 /> Mattis was the second Secretary of Defense to receive such a waiver, following [[George Marshall]].<ref name=wp20161201 /> The waiver for Mattis passed 81\u201317 in the Senate, and 268\u2013151 in the House. Mattis was subsequently confirmed as Secretary of Defense by a vote of 98\u20131 in the United States Senate on January 20, 2017.<ref name=\"WaPo confirmation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/01/20/senate-confirms-retired-gen-james-mattis-as-defense-secretary-breaking-with-decades-of-precedent/ |title=Senate confirms retired Gen. James Mattis as defense secretary, breaking with decades of precedent |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] was the sole \"no\" vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-confirms-james-mattis-as-defense-secretary-1484952996?mod=e2tw|title=Senate Confirms James Mattis as Defense Secretary |last1=Peterson |first1=Kristina |last2=Hughes |first2=Siobhan  |date=January 20, 2017 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> stating that she was opposed to the waiver on principle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/kirsten-gillibrand-mattis-waiver-232099 |title=Gillibrand says she won't vote for Mattis waiver |last=Schor |first=Elana |date=January 20, 2017 |work=[[Politico]] |quote=While I deeply respect General Mattis's service, I will oppose a waiver. Civilian control of our military is a fundamental principle of American democracy, and I will not vote for an exception to this rule.|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n[[File:JamesN.Mattis.Nurettin Canikli.JPG|thumb|Mattis and Turkish Defense Minister [[Nurettin Canikli]] at NATO headquarters in Brussels, February 2018]]\nIn a January 2017 phone call with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s deputy crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud|Mohammed bin Salman]], Mattis \"reaffirmed the importance of the [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013Saudi Arabia strategic relationship]]\".<ref>{{cite document |url=https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1066487/readout-of-secretary-mattis-call-with-kingdom-of-saudi-arabias-deputy-crown-pri |title=Readout of Secretary Mattis' Call with Kingdom of Saudi Arabia's Deputy Crown Prince and Minister of Defense Mohammed bin Salman |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201043709/https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1066487/readout-of-secretary-mattis-call-with-kingdom-of-saudi-arabias-deputy-crown-pri |archive-date=February 1, 2017 |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor his first official trip abroad, Mattis began a two-day visit with longtime U.S. ally [[South Korea]] on February 2, 2017.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" /> He warned [[North Korea]] that \"any attack on the United States, or our allies, will be defeated\", and any use of nuclear weapons would be met with an \"effective and overwhelming\" response from the United States.<ref name=\"aljazeera.com\" /> During a press conference in [[London]] on March 31, 2017, with his UK counterpart [[Secretary of State for Defence]] [[Michael Fallon]], Mattis said North Korea was behaving \"in a very reckless manner\" and must be stopped.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/defense-sec-james-mattis-north-korea-has-got-be-stopped-n740966|title=Defense Sec. James Mattis: North Korea 'Has Got to Be Stopped'|date=March 31, 2017|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=December 28, 2018 |first1=Alexander |last1=Smith |first2=Gabe|last2= Joselow }}</ref> During a Pentagon news conference on May 26, Mattis reported the U.S. was working with the UN, China, Japan, and South Korea to avoid \"a military solution\" with North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-military-solution-north-korea-would-be-tragic-2017-5|title=James Mattis says a military solution in North Korea will 'be tragic on an unbelievable scale'|date=May 26, 2017|work=Business Insider}}</ref> On June 3 Mattis said the United States regarded North Korea as \"clear and present danger\" during a speech at the international security conference in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/defense-secretary-mattis-turns-up-heat-on-north-korea-and-china/|title=Defense Secretary Mattis turns up heat on North Korea and China|date=June 3, 2017|publisher=CBS News|agency=Reuters |first1=Phil |last1=Stewart |first2=David|last2= Brunnstrom }}</ref> In a June 12 written statement to the [[House Armed Services Committee]] Mattis said North Korea was the \"most urgent and dangerous threat to peace and security\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN19407I|title=North Korea 'most urgent' threat to security: Mattis|first1=Idrees|last1=Ali |first2=Mike|last2=Stone|work=Reuters|date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> On June 15 Mattis said the U.S. would win a war against North Korea, but \"at great cost\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-north-korea-war-we-will-win-2017-6|title=Defense Secretary Mattis explains what war with North Korea would look like|date=June 16, 2017|first=Alex|last=Lockie|work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2017, during questioning from the U.S. Senate, Mattis affirmed his support for U.S. troops remaining in Iraq after the [[Battle of Mosul (2016\u20132017)|Battle of Mosul]] was concluded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/articles/mattis-troops-iraq-years-after-isis |title=Mattis: Expect U.S. troops in Iraq even after ISIS falls|date=March 22, 2017|work=Military Times|first=Leo|last=Shane III}}</ref> Mattis responded to critics who suggested the Trump administration had loosened the [[rules of engagement]] for the [[Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S. military in Iraq]] after U.S.-led coalition [[2017 Mosul airstrike|airstrikes in Mosul]] killed civilians,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-mosul-usa-idUSKBN16Y2BA |title=After civilians killed in Mosul, Pentagon denies loosening rules |date=March 27, 2017|work=Reuters}}</ref> saying, \"We go out of our way to always do everything humanly possible to reduce the loss of life or injury among innocent people.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/04/11/civilian-casualties-are-up-and-congress-is-awol/|title=Civilian casualties are up and Congress is AWOL |date=April 11, 2017 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |accessdate= December 31, 2018 |first=Micah |last= Zenko}}</ref> According to ''Airwars'', the U.S.-led coalition killed as many as 6,000 civilians in Iraq and Syria in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-deaths-tripled-in-us-led-campaign-during-2017-watchdog-alleges/2018/01/18/ccfae298-fc6d-11e7-a46b-a3614530bd87_story.html |title=Civilian deaths tripled in U.S.-led campaign against ISIS in 2017, watchdog alleges |url-status=live |first=Missy |last=Ryan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430183007/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-deaths-tripled-in-us-led-campaign-during-2017-watchdog-alleges/2018/01/18/ccfae298-fc6d-11e7-a46b-a3614530bd87_story.html |archive-date=April 30, 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:SD visits Australia 170605-D-GY869-1426 (34320481913).jpg|thumb|Mattis and [[Marise Payne]] inspecting the [[Australia's Federation Guard]] in [[Sydney]].]]\nOn April 5, 2017, Mattis called the [[Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]] \"a heinous act,\" and said it would be treated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news|first=Carlos |last=Mu\u00f1oz |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/apr/5/mattis-condemns-heinous-chemical-attack-syria/|title=Defense Secretary Mattis condemns 'heinous' chemical attack in Syria, DoD mulls response|date=April 5, 2017|work=Washington Times}}</ref> On April 10 Mattis warned the Syrian government against using [[Chemical warfare|chemical weapons]] again.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement by Secretary of Defense James Mattis on the U.S. Military Response to the Syrian Government's Use of Chemical Weapons|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1146758/statement-by-secretary-of-defense-James-mattis-on-the-us-military-response-to-the/|publisher=United States Department of Defense|date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The following day, Mattis gave his first Pentagon news conference since becoming Secretary of Defense, saying [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]'s defeat remained \"our priority,\" and the Syrian government would pay a \"very, very stiff price\" for further usage of chemical weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/mattis-syria-policy-defeat-isis-237122|title=Mattis: U.S. Syria policy is still to defeat ISIS|first=Jacqueline|last=Klimas|date=April 11, 2017|work=Politico}}</ref> On April 21 Mattis said Syria still had chemical weapons and was in violation of United Nations Security Council resolutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/us-defense-secy-mattis-syria-chemical-weapons-46931091|title=US Defense Sec'y Mattis: Syria still has chemical weapons|first=Robert|last=Burns|publisher=ABC News|date=April 21, 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421221230/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/us-defense-secy-mattis-syria-chemical-weapons-46931091|archivedate=April 21, 2017}}</ref> According to investigative journalist [[Bob Woodward]], Trump ordered Mattis to assassinate Assad, but Mattis refused.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump wanted Syria's Assad assassinated, Bob Woodward claims in extraordinary new book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-bob-woodward-fear-book-syria-assad-kill-claims-a8523176.html |work=Independent |date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> On May 8 Mattis told reporters details of the proposed Syrian safe zones were \"all in process right now\" and the United States was involved with configuring them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/332366-mattis-questions-unanswered-on-syria-cease-fire-plan|title=Mattis: Questions unanswered on Syria cease-fire plan|first=Ellen|last=Mitchell|date=May 8, 2017|work=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nMattis voiced support for a [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi Arabian-led military campaign]] against [[Yemen]]'s [[Zaidiyyah|Shiite]] rebels.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/26/pentagon-weighs-more-support-for-saudi-led-war-in-yemen/ |title=Pentagon Weighs More Support for Saudi-led War in Yemen |date=March 26, 2017|work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> He asked Trump to remove restrictions on U.S. military support for Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-administration-weighs-deeper-involvement-in-yemen-war/2017/03/26/b81eecd8-0e49-11e7-9d5a-a83e627dc120_story.html |title=Trump administration weighs deeper involvement in Yemen war |date=March 26, 2017|work=The Washington Post|first1=Karen |last1=DeYoung |first2=Missy|last2=Ryan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2017, one week after the [[2017 Nangarhar airstrike|Nangarhar airstrike]], Mattis told reporters that the U.S. would not conduct a damage assessment \"in terms of the number of people killed\" in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/20/James-mattis-mother-of-all-bombs-afghanistan-damage-237413|title=Mattis: U.S. won't dig into 'mother of all bombs' damage in Afghanistan|first=Jacqueline|last=Klimas|date=April 20, 2017|work=Politico}}</ref> Mattis traveled to Afghanistan days later and met with government officials, explaining that the purpose of the trip was to allow him to state his recommendations for U.S. strategy in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/24/politics/mattis-afghanistan-visit/ |title=US Defense Secretary Mattis visits Afghanistan|first1=Susannah|last1=Cullinane|first2=Ryan|last2=Browne |publisher=CNN|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref> On June 13, Mattis said U.S. forces were \"not winning\" in Afghanistan and the administration would develop a new strategy by \"mid-July\" while speaking to the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/13/James-mattis-not-winning-afghanistan-239488|title=Mattis: 'We are not winning in Afghanistan'|first=Connor|last=O'Brien|date=June 13, 2017|publisher=Politico}}</ref> On June 27 Mattis told reporters that he was creating a conflict-ending strategy for Afghanistan that would also \"remove the danger to the Afghan people and to us and to all the nations that have been attacked by terrorist groups out of that region\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pjmedia.com/news-and-politics/2017/06/27/mattis-crafting-strategy-to-remove-the-danger-to-the-afghan-people-and-to-us/|title=Mattis Crafting Strategy to 'Remove the Danger to the Afghan People and to Us'|first=Bridget|last=Johnson|publisher=PJMedia.com |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> On June 29 Mattis said the Obama administration \"may have pulled our troops out too rapidly\" and that he intended to submit a new Afghanistan strategy to Trump upon his return to Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/29/mattis-says-us-may-have-pulled-our-troops-out-too-rapidly-in-afghanistan.html|title=Mattis says US 'may have pulled our troops out too rapidly' in Afghanistan|date=June 29, 2017|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\nThe United States has been openly arming the [[Syrian Democratic Forces|Syrian Kurdish]] fighters in the war against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] since May 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/turkey-joins-syria-chaos-us-tries-find-someone-hold-peace-kurds-786828 |title=Turkish Forces Bomb Key U.S. Ally In Fight Against ISIS In Syria |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215025525/http://www.newsweek.com/turkey-joins-syria-chaos-us-tries-find-someone-hold-peace-kurds-786828 |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=January 22, 2018 |first=Zachary |last=Fryer-Biggs}}</ref> Following the start of the [[Operation Olive Branch|Turkish invasion of northern Syria]] aimed at ousting U.S.-backed Syrian Kurds from the enclave of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]], Mattis said in January 2018: \"Turkey is a NATO ally. It's the only NATO country with an active insurgency inside its borders. And Turkey has legitimate security concerns.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-legitimate-security-concerns-mattis-126090 |title= Turkey has legitimate security concerns: Mattis |agency=Andalou Agency |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215083638/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-legitimate-security-concerns-mattis-126090 |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |work= [[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> Turkish Deputy Prime Minister [[Bekir Bozda\u011f]] urged the United States to halt its support for Kurdish [[People's Protection Units|YPG]] fighters, saying: \"Those who support the terrorist organization will become a target in this battle.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/01/turkey-stop-ypg-support-face-confrontation-180125182540759.html|title=Turkey to US: Stop YPG support or face 'confrontation' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213150333/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/01/turkey-stop-ypg-support-face-confrontation-180125182540759.html |archive-date=February 13, 2018 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Resignation-Letter-From-Secretary-James-N-Mattis.pdf|thumb|Resignation letter from Secretary James Mattis]]\nIn November 2018 the [[CIA]] assessed with \"high confidence\" that [[Saudi Arabia]]'s Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] ordered the assassination of [[The Washington Post|''Washington Post'']] columnist [[Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref>{{cite web |title=White House Digs Itself in Deeper on Khashoggi |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/12/04/white-house-digs-itself-in-deeper-on-khashoggi-trump-refuses-to-address-murder-journalist-saudi-arabia-anger-congress-mohammed-bin-salman-complicit-war-in-yemen-humanitarian-disaster-gina-haspel/ |work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=December 4, 2018|first1=Michael |last1=Hirsh |first2=Robbie |last2=Gramer}}</ref> Under mounting pressure from lawmakers who wanted action against Saudi Arabia, Mattis and Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]], in a rare closed briefing of the Senate, disputed the CIA's conclusion and declared there was no direct evidence linking the Crown Prince to Khashoggi's assassination.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump administration defends close Saudi ties as Senate moves to end US support for Yemen war |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/28/us-cabinet-members-defend-close-saudi-ties-lawmakers-unconvinced.html |publisher=CNBC |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2018, Trump announced immediate [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|U.S. withdrawal from Syria]], over the objections of his national security advisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/20/623246756/defense-secretary-mattis-to-retire-in-february-trump-says|title=Defense Secretary Mattis To Retire In February, Trump Says, Amid Syria Tension|publisher=NPR|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> Mattis had recently said that the U.S. would remain in Syria following the defeat of ISIL to ensure they did not regroup. The next day, he submitted his resignation after failing to persuade Trump to reconsider.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/19/678150756/reports-white-house-intends-to-pull-u-s-troops-from-syria|title=White House Orders Pentagon To Pull U.S. Troops From Syria|publisher=NPR|accessdate=December 20, 2018 |quote= The troop withdrawal is a reversal of policy discussed as recently as this month by Mattis, who said that after the defeat of ISIS, U.S. forces would remain in Syria to prevent a resurgence of the terrorist group and to counteract Iran.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html|title=Jim Mattis Resigns, Rebuking Trump's Worldview|first=Helene |last=Cooper|date=December 20, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref> His resignation letter contained language that appeared to criticize Trump's worldview\u2014praising NATO, which Trump has often derided, and the 79-nation Defeat-ISIS coalition that Trump had just decided to abandon. Mattis also affirmed the need for \"treating allies with respect and also being clear-eyed about both malign actors and strategic competitors,\" and remaining \"resolute and unambiguous\" against authoritarian states such as China and Russia. He wrote that Trump has \"the right to have a Secretary of Defense whose views are better aligned with [his] on these and other subjects.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html|title=Jim Mattis, Defense Secretary, Resigns in Rebuke of Trump\u2019s Worldview|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=December 8, 2018|accessdate=December 21, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-sad-day-for-america-washington-fears-a-trump-unchecked-by-mattis/2018/12/20/faef8da0-04ac-11e9-b6a9-0aa5c2fcc9e4_story.html|title=\u2018A sad day for America\u2019: Washington fears a Trump unchecked by Mattis|first1=Greg|last1=Jaffe|first2=Karoun|last2=Demirjian|date=December 20, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> His resignation triggered alarm among historical allies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://on.ft.com/2Cuv6tY|title= Mattis Resignation Spreads Alarm in Washington and Abroad|first=Demetri|last=Sevastopulo|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=December 23, 2018|work=Financial Times}}</ref> Mattis's letter said his resignation would be effective February 28, 2019.<ref name=nyt20181220>{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Helene |work=The New York Times |title=Jim Mattis, Marine General Turned Defense Secretary, Will Leave Pentagon in February |date=December 20, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html}}</ref> Three days later Trump moved Mattis's departure date up to January 1, after becoming angered by the implicit criticism of Trump's worldview in the resignation letter.<ref name=\"angry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/23/us/politics/trump-mattis.html|title=Trump, Angry Over Mattis's Rebuke, Removes Him 2 Months Early|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=23 December 2018|work =The New York Times}}</ref> On January 2, 2019, Trump criticized Mattis's performance as Secretary of Defense and said he had \"essentially fired him.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/02/us/politics/trump-mattis-defense-secretary-generals.html|title=Trump Says Mattis Resignation Was \u2018Essentially\u2019 a Firing, Escalating His New Front Against Military Critics|first=Maggie|last=Haberman|date=January 2, 2019|newspaper =New York Times |accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPost-tenure at the October 17, 2019 [[Alfred E. Smith Memorial Foundation Dinner]], keynote speaker Mattis responded to comments Trump made about him, saying, \"I\u2019m not just an overrated general, I am the greatest, the world\u2019s most overrated...I\u2019m honored to be considered that by Donald Trump, because he also called [[Meryl Streep]] an overrated actress. So I guess I\u2019m the Meryl Streep of generals, and frankly, that sounds pretty good to me. And you do have to admit that between me and Meryl, at least we've had some victories.\" He continued, \"I've earned my spurs on the battlefield...Donald Trump earned his spurs in a letter from a doctor.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2019/10/18/us/mattis-trump.html |work=The New York Times |title=Mattis Mocks Trump\u2019s Bone Spurs and Love of Fast Food |first=Christine |last=Hauser |date=October 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jim-mattis-slams-donald-trump-during-speech-al-smith-dinner-2019-10-18 |work=CBS News |title=Jim Mattis fires back at President Trump for \"overrated\" insult |first=Grace |last=Segers |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n=== Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process ===\nMattis supports a [[two-state solution]] model for [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process|Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace]]. He has said the situation in Israel is \"unsustainable\" and that [[Israeli settlement]]s harm prospects for peace and could lead to an apartheid-like situation in the [[West Bank]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/trumps-top-pentagon-pick-said-settlements-were-creating-apartheid/ |title= Trump's top Pentagon pick said settlements were creating 'apartheid' |work=Times of Israel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122180032/http://www.timesofisrael.com/trumps-top-pentagon-pick-said-settlements-were-creating-apartheid |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |first=Eric |last=Cortellessa |date=November 20, 2016}}</ref> In particular, he has said that the perception of biased American support for Israel has made it difficult for moderate Arabs to show support for the United States. Mattis strongly supported Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] on the Middle East peace process, praising Kerry for being \"wisely focused like a laser beam\" on a two-state solution.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/ex-us-general-we-pay-a-price-for-backing-israel |title =Ex-US general: We pay a price for backing Israel |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120155623/http://www.timesofisrael.com/ex-us-general-we-pay-a-price-for-backing-israel |archive-date=November 20, 2016 |first=Lazar |last=Berman |date=July 25, 2013 |work=Times of Israel|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Iran and Middle Eastern allies ===\n[[File:SD meets with Egypt's President 170405-D-SV709-331 (33705568522).jpg|thumb|Mattis and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] in April 2017]]\nMattis believes [[Iran]] is the principal threat to the stability of the Middle East, ahead of [[Al-Qaeda]] and [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]. Mattis says: \"I consider ISIS nothing more than an excuse for Iran to continue its mischief. Iran is not an enemy of ISIS. They have a lot to gain from the turmoil in the region that ISIS creates.\" Mattis sees the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran nuclear deal]] as a poor agreement, but believes there is now no way to tear it up, saying: \"We are just going to have to recognize that we have an imperfect arms control agreement. Second, that what we achieved is a nuclear pause, not a nuclear halt\". Mattis argues that inspections may fail to prevent Iran from seeking to develop nuclear weapons, but that \"[i]f nothing else at least we will have better targeting data if it comes to a fight in the future.\"<ref name=\"Washington Examiner\" /> Additionally, he criticized Obama for being \"naive\" about Iranian intentions and Congress for being \"pretty much absent\" on the nuclear deal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shane III|first1=Leo|title=General Mattis wants Iran to be a top focus for the next president (whoever it is)|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/story/military/2016/04/22/mattis-csis-speech-iran/83397134/ |accessdate=December 2, 2016|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Sightline Media Group|Military Times]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Defense Secretary James Mattis & Deputy Crown Price of Saudi Arabia Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud in the Pentagon in Washington, D.C., March 16, 2017 (33323866082).jpg|thumb|Mattis with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s prince [[Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud|Mohammad]] in March 2017]]\nMattis praises the friendship of regional US allies such as [[Jordan]], [[Israel]], and the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=\"defense.gov1\">{{cite news|last1=Cronk|first1=Terri Moon|title=Mattis Praises America\u2019s Security Partnership With Israel\n|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1159485/mattis-praises-americas-security-partnership-with-israel/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018|date=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"defense.gov2\">{{cite news|last1=Cronk|first1=Terri Moon|title=Mattis, Israeli Counterpart Discuss Mutual Security Concerns|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1504866/mattis-israeli-counterpart-discuss-mutual-security-concerns/\n|accessdate=August 19, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"military.com\">{{cite news|last1=Seck|first1=Hope Hodge|title=Mattis: 'I Don't Understand' Speculation about Presidential Run|url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2016/04/22/mattis-i-dont-understand-speculation-about-presidential-run.html|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=military.com|date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> He also criticized Obama for seeing allies as \"free-loading\", saying: \"For a sitting U.S. President to see our allies as freeloaders is nuts.\"<ref name=\"military.com\" /> He has cited the importance of the United Arab Emirates and Jordan as countries that wanted to help, for example, in filling in the gaps in Afghanistan. He criticized Obama's defense strategy as giving \"the perception we're pulling back\" from US allies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grady|first1=John|title=Mattis: U.S. Suffering 'Strategic Atrophy'|url=https://news.usni.org/2015/05/14/mattis-u-s-suffering-strategic-atrophy|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=USNI News|publisher=U.S. Naval Institute|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> He stresses the need for the US to bolster its ties with allied intelligence agencies, particularly those of Jordan, [[Egypt]] and [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mu\u00f1oz|first1=Carlo|title=James Mattis, retired Marine general, says Iran nuclear deal 'fell short'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/22/james-mattis-retired-marine-general-says-iran-nucl/|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=The Washington Times|date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> In 2012 Mattis argued for providing weapons to [[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War|Syrian rebels]] as a way to fight back against [[Iranian involvement in the Syrian Civil War|Iranian proxies in Syria]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ackerman|first1=Spencer|title=Military's Mideast Chief Sounds Ready to Aid Syria's Rebels|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/03/mattis-syria|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe departure of several of Mattis's senior deputies in the fall of 2018 caused concern in foreign policy circles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/31/pentagon-nato-policy-chief-steps-down-dod-defense-mattis/|title=Three Senior Pentagon Officials Leave in Quick Succession|first=Lara Seligman, Robbie|last=Gramer|publisher=|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> Many senior officials served only because of Mattis and fought political battles with the White House regularly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/15/us/politics/jim-mattis-trump-defense-relationship.html|title=Fraying Ties With Trump Put Jim Mattis\u2019s Fate in Doubt|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=September 15, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> One of the most serious areas of concern has been the potential for war with Iran because of the Trump Administration's withdrawal from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|JCPOA]] at the same time the U.S. military is redeploying forces from the Middle East to the Pacific to better compete with China and contain North Korea.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 3, 2018 |accessdate=December 28, 2018|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/military-officials-alarmed-about-shrinking-military-footprint-in-middle-east-as-administration-pressures-iran/2018/11/03/44e599f4-b152-4fdc-938e-744fa5e3d6fe_story.html |title=Citing Iran, military officials are alarmed by shrinking U.S. footprint in Middle East|work=Washington Post }}</ref> Mattis opposed the withdrawal from the JCPOA, calling the deal \"the best we could come up with\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mattis-iran-is-the-biggest-threat-to-mideast-peace|title=Mattis: Iran is the biggest threat to Mideast peace|date=April 22, 2016|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\nDuring an interview on C-SPAN, the Deputy for Middle East [[Mick Mulroy]] said that Mattis focused on five distinct threats posed by Iran. The first was obtaining a nuclear weapon. The second was to maritime security in the [[Strait of Hormuz]] and the [[Bab al-Mandab]], because a substantial portion of energy trade and commercial goods go through those areas. The third was their support to proxies and terrorist organizations, including [[Hezbollah]] in Lebanon and Syria, [[Houthis]] in Yemen, some [[Hashd al-Shaabi]] in Iraq and safe-harboring senior [[al-Qaeda]] leaders in Iran. The fourth was Iranian ballistic missiles in Houthi-controlled areas of Yemen for use against Saudi Arabia and in Syria with Hezbollah to use against Israel. Cyber was the fifth threat and a growing concern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?460180-2/syria-middle-east-security-michael-mulroy-remarks|title=Syria and Middle East Security, Michael Mulroy Remarks &#124; C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Japan ===\nMattis visited [[Japan]] one week after being sworn in as Secretary of Defense. During a meeting with [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] [[Shinz\u014d Abe]], Mattis emphasized that the U.S. remains [[Treaty of Mutual Cooperation and Security Between the United States and Japan|committed to the mutual defense of Japan]] and stated, \"I want there to be no misunderstanding during the transition in Washington that we stand firmly, 100 percent, shoulder to shoulder with you and the Japanese people.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Michael R.|last2=Rich|first2=Motoko|title=James Mattis Says U.S. Is 'Shoulder to Shoulder' With Japan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/03/world/asia/us-japan-mattis-abe-defense.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> He also reassured Japan that the U.S. would defend the disputed [[Senkaku Islands dispute|Senkaku Islands]] controlled by Japan but also claimed by China and [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/china-usa-japan-senkaku-islands-dispute-stability-security-region-james-mattis-donald-trump-a7562491.html |title=China accuses US of putting regional stability at risk over backing of Japan in island dispute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926143120/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/china-usa-japan-senkaku-islands-dispute-stability-security-region-james-mattis-donald-trump-a7562491.html |archive-date=September 26, 2017 |work=The Independent |date=February 4, 2017|first=Rebecca |last=Flood}}</ref>\n\n=== Russia ===\nSpeaking at a conference sponsored by [[The Heritage Foundation]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] in 2015, Mattis said he believed that [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]]'s intent is \"to break NATO apart.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters|url=http://www.unian.info/world/1632767-general-stating-russian-aggression-in-ukraine-much-more-severe-than-ustreats-it-may-become-defense-secretary.html |title=General stating Russian aggression in Ukraine \"much more severe\" than U.S. treats it may become Defense Secretary |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206030025/http://www.unian.info/world/1632767-general-stating-russian-aggression-in-ukraine-much-more-severe-than-ustreats-it-may-become-defense-secretary.html |archive-date=December 6, 2016 |publisher=[[UNIAN]] |date=November 19, 2016}}</ref> Mattis has also spoken out against what he perceives as Russia's expansionist or bellicose policies in [[Russian military intervention in Syria|Syria]], [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Ukraine]] and the [[Baltic states]].<ref>{{cite news |url-status=live|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/us/politics/james-mattis-secrtary-of-defense-trump.html |title=James Mattis, Outspoken Retired Marine, Is Trump's Choice as Defense Secretary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301210650/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/us/politics/james-mattis-secrtary-of-defense-trump.html |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |work=New York Times |date=December 1, 2016 |first1=Michael R. |last =Gordon |first2=Eric |last2=Schmitt}}</ref> In 2017 Mattis said that the world order is \"under biggest attacks since World War Two, from Russia, terrorist groups, and China's actions in the [[South China Sea]].\"<ref name=\"Press TV\" />\n\nOn February 16, 2017, Mattis said the United States was not currently prepared to collaborate with Russia on military matters, including future anti-[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] U.S. operations.<ref name=\"baldor\" /> In August 2017, he said: \"Despite Russia's denials, we know they are seeking to redraw international borders by force, undermining the sovereign and free nations of Europe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/russia-lies-about-not-wanting-redraw-map-europe-force-mattis-tells-ukraine-655034|title=James Mattis says Russia wants to use violence to redraw the borders of Europe|date=August 25, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2018 resignation letter, Mattis called both Russia and China \"authoritarian models\" rivaling U.S. interests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46644841|title=James Mattis' resignation letter in full|date=December 21, 2018|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretaries Tillerson and Mattis Host the U.S.-China Diplomatic and Security Dialogue With Chinese State Councilor Yang and General Fang in Washington (34604966264).jpg|thumb|Mattis and Tillerson with Chinese General [[Fang Fenghui]] and State Councilor [[Yang Jiechi]], June 2017]]\n\n=== China ===\nMattis called for [[freedom of navigation]] in the South China Sea and criticized China's [[Great Wall of Sand|island-building]] activities, saying: \"The bottom line is [...] the international waters are international waters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Katie|title=Chinese state media slams Tillerson over South China Sea|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/01/13/politics/us-tillerson-china-reaction/|accessdate=February 8, 2017|publisher=CNN Politics|date=January 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate change ===\n{{See also|Climate security}}\nIn 2017, Mattis said that budget cuts would hamper the ability to monitor the [[effects of global warming]],<ref name=\"Union of Concerned Scientists\" /> and noted, \"climate change is a challenge that requires a broader, whole-of-government response.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/james-mattis-us-defence-secretary-climate-change-destabilise-world-security-donald-trump-global-a7630676.html|title=US Defence Secretary James Mattis says climate change is already destabilising the world |year=2017 |work=The Independent}}</ref> He also told senators \"climate change is impacting stability in areas of the world where our troops are operating today.\"<ref>Ness, Erik \"The Cost of Skepticism,\" ''Brown Alumni Monthly,'' March/April 2018, p.16</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMattis has never been married<ref name=WSJ_Cooper /> and has no children.<ref name=Kovach /> He proposed to a woman, but she called off the wedding days before it was to occur, not wanting to burden his career.<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /> He is nicknamed \"The Warrior Monk\" because of his bachelorhood and lifelong devotion to the study of war.<ref name=Ollie>{{cite news|author=[[Oliver North|North, Oliver]] |title=Gen. Mattis: The Warrior Monk |url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2010/07/09/gen-mattis-the-warrior-monk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118093128/http://insider.foxnews.com/2010/07/09/gen-mattis-the-warrior-monk |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 3, 2015 |work=Fox News Insider |date=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> An avid reader, he has 7000 books in his private library,<ref>[[Bob Woodward]], ''[[Fear: Trump in the White House]]'', Simon and Schuster, 2019, p. 50</ref> and has recommended [[Marcus Aurelius]]'s ''[[Meditations]]'' as the one book every American should read.<ref>Paul Szoldra (26 September 2018), [https://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-says-every-american-should-read-this-one-book-2018-9?IR=T \"Mattis says every American should read this one book\"], ''Business Insider''. Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref>\n\nMattis is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], and has been described as \"devout\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-john-kelly-trump-gets-a-plain-spoken-disciplinarian-as-his-chief-of-staff/2017/07/28/0c29cfc2-73db-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|title=In John Kelly, Trump gets a plain-spoken disciplinarian as his chief of staff|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|date=July 28, 2017|work=The Washington Post|access-date=June 16, 2018|last2=deGrandpre|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612234108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-john-kelly-trump-gets-a-plain-spoken-disciplinarian-as-his-chief-of-staff/2017/07/28/0c29cfc2-73db-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"committed.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/trumps-catholic-warriors|title=Trump\u2019s Catholic Warriors|work=National Catholic Register|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015449/http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/trumps-catholic-warriors|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 Iraq invasion]], he often prayed with general [[John F. Kelly]] on Sundays.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Trump transition team's formal biography of Mattis described him as \"the living embodiment of the Marine Corps motto, ''[[Semper fidelis|Semper Fidelis]]''.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> He has declined when asked by reporters to discuss his faith in public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/12/04/mattis-shows-how-to-handle-a-reporters-question-about-his-religious-beliefs/|title=Mattis Shows How to Handle a Reporter\u2019s Question About His Religious Beliefs|website=Foreign Policy|quote=That's something I stay pretty private about.| access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015603/https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/12/04/mattis-shows-how-to-handle-a-reporters-question-about-his-religious-beliefs/|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2003 PBS interview, Mattis recalled how his Marines followed advice from his chaplain on gaining the support of Iraqi citizens: \"On the suggestion of my Catholic chaplain the Marines would take chilled drinking water in bottles and walk out amongst the protesters and hand it out. It is just hard to throw a rock at somebody who has given you a cold drink of water and it's 120 degrees outside.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Military awards ==\nMattis's decorations, awards, and badges include, among others:\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}&nbsp;[[File:Navy Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]&nbsp;[[File:US Defense Superior Service Medal ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]][[File:Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|other_device=nv|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=award-star|ribbon=Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Combat Action Ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:U.S. Navy Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|[[File:Marine Corps Expeditionary ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Southwest Asia Service Medal ribbon (1991-2016).svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Afghanistan Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Humanitarian Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=6|type=service-star|other_device=bss|ribbon=Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Recruiting Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:POL Z\u0142oty Medal Wojska Polskiego BAR.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=NATO Meritorious Service Medal bar.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:MSC ribbon-military.png|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Kuwait Liberation Medal (Saudi Arabia) ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Kuwait Liberation Medal (Kuwait) ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:USMC Rifle Expert badge.png|150px]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:USMC Pistol Expert badge.png|150px]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge.png|150px]]\n|}\n</center>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!1st row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] w/ one [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n!2nd row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Bronze Star Medal]] w/ [[Combat \"V\"]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ two [[5/16 inch star|{{frac|5|16}}\" Gold Star]]s\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]\n|-\n!3rd row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy and Marine Corps Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Navy Unit Commendation]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Unit Commendation|Navy and Marine Corps Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n|-\n!4th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marine Corps Expeditionary Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[National Defense Service Medal]] w/ two [[service star|{{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] w/ two {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|-\n!5th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n|-\n!6th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Sea Service Ribbon]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" silver star and two {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Recruiting Service Ribbon#United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps Recruiting Service Ribbon]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Polish Army Medal]] in gold\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[NATO Medal|NATO Meritorious Service Medal]]<ref name=\"NATOawards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.act.nato.int/french-general-assumes-command-of-allied-command-transformation|title=French general assumes command of Allied Command Transformation|date=September 18, 2009|work=Allied Command Transformation Public Affairs Office|publisher=[[NATO]]|accessdate=September 28, 2009|location={{USS|George Washington|CVN-73}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006090257/http://www.act.nato.int/french-general-assumes-command-of-allied-command-transformation|archive-date=October 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n!7th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[NATO Medal]] for Service with ISAF<ref name=\"NATOawards\" />\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"Text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Service Cross]] from Canada in 2013 <ref>http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2013/2013-04-27/html/gh-rg-eng.html#c101</ref>\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Kuwait Liberation Medal (Saudi Arabia)]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Kuwait Liberation Medal (Kuwait)]]\n|-\n!Badges\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Rifle Expert Badge]] (4th award)\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Pistol Expert Badge]] (2nd award)\n|-\n!Badge\n|colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]]\n|}\n</center>\n\nHis citation for the Canadian [[Meritorious Service Cross]] reads as follows: \"While occupying key leadership positions within the United States Armed Forces and NATO between 2001 and 2012, General Mattis directly and repeatedly contributed to the Canadian Forces\u2019 operational success in Afghanistan. Providing unprecedented access and championing Canadian participation in critical policy and training events, he helped shape Canadian counter-insurgency doctrine. Demonstrating unequivocal support and unwavering commitment to Canada, General Mattis has significantly strengthened Canadian-American relations and has been a critical enabler in both countries\u2019 shared achievements in Afghanistan.\"<ref>http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2013/2013-04-27/html/gh-rg-eng.html#c101</ref>\n\n== Civilian awards ==\n[[File:Defense.gov photo essay 100428-N-0696M-076.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Mattis receiving the Distinguished Military Leadership Award from [[Michael Mullen]] at the annual Atlantic Council Awards Gala in Washington, D.C.]]\n\nMattis's civilian awards include:\n\n* 2009: [[Center for National Policy]]'s [[Center for National Policy#Edmund S. Muskie Distinguished Public Service Award|Edmund S. Muskie Distinguished Public Service Award]]<ref name=SenateNom />\n* 2010: [[Atlantic Council]]'s Distinguished Military Leadership Award<ref name=SenateNom />\n* 2013: World Affairs Council of Greater Hampton Roads \"[[Ryan Crocker|Ryan C. Crocker]] Global Citizen of the Year\" Award<ref name=FWA />\n* 2014: Marine Corps University Foundation Semper Fidelis Award<ref name=FWA />\n* 2014: [[Washington College]] honorary [[Doctor of Law#United States|doctor of laws]] degree<ref>{{cite web|title=Convocation Will Honor Marine General James Mattis|url=https://www.washcoll.edu/live/news/5053-convocation-will-honor-marine-general-james-mattis|publisher=Washington College|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[Washington Policy Center]] Champion of Freedom Award recipient<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpolicy.org/publications/detail/wpcs-2016-champion-of-freedom-named-secretary-of-defense|title=WPC's 2016 'Champion of Freedom' named Secretary of Defense|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Washington Policy Center|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* Mattis is the primary subject of [[Guy Snodgrass]]'s 2019 book ''Holding the Line: Inside Trump's Pentagon with Secretary Mattis''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Holding-Line-Inside-Pentagon-Secretary/dp/0593084373|title=Holding the Line: Inside Trump's Pentagon with Secretary Mattis|last=|first=|date=|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n*[[Robert John Burke]] portrays Mattis in the 2008 HBO miniseries [[Generation Kill (miniseries)|''Generation Kill'']], which depicts the 2003 invasion of Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/generation-kill/cast-and-crew/maj-gen-james-mattis/index.html|title=Maj. Gen. James 'Maddog' Mattis|website=HBO}}</ref>\n* Mattis is also known for the [[Internet meme]] depicting him as \"Saint Mattis of Quantico, Patron Saint of Chaos\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szoldra|first1=Paul|title=The Facebook page for Marine Special Ops posted a picture of 'Mad Dog' Mattis as a saint|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/marsoc-facebook-mattis-saint-2016-12|accessdate=January 25, 2017|work=Business Insider|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* Mattis is commonly \"reported on\" by the military [[satire]] website ''[[Duffel Blog]]'' for potentially being fired,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2018/09/mattis-says-hes-absolutely-not-leaving-pentagon-while-carrying-cardboard-box-out-to-his-car/|title=Mattis says he\u2019s \u2018absolutely not\u2019 leaving Pentagon while carrying cardboard box out to his car|first=Paul|last=Sharpe|date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> winning an \"arms race\" with Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2017/03/winning-arms-race-says-mattis-workout-kremlin-gym/|title=\u2018We\u2019re winning this arms race,\u2019 Mattis says during workout at Kremlin gym|first=Cat|last=Astronaut|date=March 2, 2017}}</ref> and crossing the Potomac to launch a Roman-style ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2013/12/general-mattis-crosses-potomac-100000-troops-president-senate-flee-city/|title=General Mattis Crosses Potomac With 100,000 Troops; President, Senate Flee City|last=Scuttlebutt|first=Dick|date=December 24, 2013|website=Duffel Blog|language=en-US|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref>\n*Mattis is an avid reader and releases his [https://mattisbooks.com/ reading lists].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/13/defense-secretary-james-mattis-extraordinary-reading-habits.html|title=The extraordinary reading habits of Defense Secretary James Mattis|last=Macias|first=Amanda|date=2018-09-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of United States Marine Corps four-star generals]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Marine Corps}}\n* Reynolds, Nicholas E. (2005). ''Basrah, Baghdad and Beyond: The U.S. Marine Corps in the Second Iraq War''. p.&nbsp;5. Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|1-59114-717-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |commons=Category:James N. Mattis|q=James Mattis|d=Q267902|b=no|n=no|s=Author:James N. Mattis|v=no|wikt=no}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171011204823/http://www.quotes.euronews.com/people/james-mattis-nxa8qYBW Quotes from James Mattis on ''All Views by Quotes'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z_xCQ40FOto James Mattis Sworn in As US Secretary of Defense]\n* [https://www.defense.gov/About-DoD/Biographies/Biography-View/Article/1055835/james-mattis Department of Defense biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430125117/https://slsp.manpower.usmc.mil/gosa/biographies/rptBiography.asp?PERSON_ID=121&PERSON_TYPE=General Official Marine Corps biography]\n* {{cite news|date=June 2017 |url=http://mihsislander.org/2017/06/full-transcript-james-mattis-interview/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916053803/http://mihsislander.org/2017/06/full-transcript-james-mattis-interview/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 16, 2018 | title= Full transcript: Defense Secretary James Mattis' interview with The Islander}}\n* {{C-SPAN|jamesmattis}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Lance L. Smith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander of Transformation]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[St\u00e9phane Abrial]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=Commander of [[United States Joint Forces Command]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=Keith Huber<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John R. Allen]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commander of [[United States Central Command]]|years=2010\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lloyd Austin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ash Carter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of Defense]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Esper]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{CentComHeads}}\n{{USSecDef}}\n{{Trump cabinet}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mattis, James Norman}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Gulf War]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American Marine Corps personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American people of Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Central Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hoover Institution people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:National War College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Pullman, Washington]]\n[[Category:People from Richland, Washington]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NATO Meritorious Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Polish Army Medal]]\n[[Category:Theranos people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps generals]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of Defense]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Meritorious Service Medal (United States)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former US Secretary of Defense and retired US Marine Corps general}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = James Mattis official photo.jpg\n| office = 26th [[United States Secretary of Defense]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy = [[Robert O. Work]]<br />[[Patrick M. Shanahan]]\n| term_start = January 20, 2017\n| term_end = January 1, 2019\n| predecessor = [[Ash Carter]]\n| successor = [[Mark Esper]]\n| office1 = Commander of the [[United States Central Command]]\n| president1 = [[Barack Obama]]\n| term_start1 = August 11, 2010\n| term_end1 = March 22, 2013\n| predecessor1 = [[David Petraeus]]\n| successor1 = [[Lloyd Austin]]\n| office2 = Commander of the [[United States Joint Forces Command]]\n| president2 = {{ubl|[[George W. Bush]]|Barack Obama}}\n| term_start2 = November 9, 2007\n| term_end2 = August 11, 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[Lance L. Smith]]\n| successor2 = [[Raymond T. Odierno]]\n| office3 = [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]\n| deputy3 = [[Luciano Zappata]]\n| term_start3 = November 9, 2007\n| term_end3 = September 8, 2009\n| predecessor3 = Lance L. Smith\n| successor3 = [[St\u00e9phane Abrial]]\n| birth_name = James Norman Mattis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1950|9|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Pullman, Washington|Pullman]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = <!-- Don't insert an entry here unless you have a citation for it. -->\n| education = {{ubl|[[Central Washington University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])|[[National Defense University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])}}\n| net_worth = $5 million<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's What Each Member Of Trump's $4.5 Billion Cabinet Is Worth |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chasewithorn/2016/12/22/heres-how-much-trumps-cabinet-is-really-worth/#3b5c6faf7169 |first=Chase |last=Peterson-Withorn |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n| signature = James N. Mattis Signature.svg\n| nickname = {{unbulleted list|\"Chaos\" (callsign)<ref name=Kovach>{{cite news |last1=Kovach |first1=Gretel C. |title=Just don't call him Mad Dog |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-just-dont-call-him-mad-dog-2013jan19-story.html |accessdate=November 20, 2016 |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=January 19, 2013|quote=He is a lifelong bachelor with no children, but wouldn't move into a monastery unless it was stocked with \"beer and ladies.\"}}</ref>|\"[[Warrior Monk]]\"<ref name=Kovach /><ref name=ArmedForceJournal>{{cite web |url=http://www.armedforcesjournal.com/the-corps-should-look-to-its-small-wars-past/ |accessdate=July 29, 2014 |title=The Corps should look to its small-wars past |authorlink=Max Boot |last=Boot |first=Max |work=[[Armed Forces Journal]] |date=March 2006}}</ref>|\"Mad Dog\"<ref name=ArmedForceJournal />}}\n| allegiance = United States\n| branch = [[United States Marine Corps]]\n| serviceyears = 1969\u20132013\n| rank = {{Dodseal|USMCO10}} [[General (United States)|General]]\n| commands = {{unbulleted list|[[United States Central Command]]|[[United States Joint Forces Command]]|[[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]|[[I Marine Expeditionary Force]]|[[United States Marine Forces Central Command]]|[[Marine Corps Combat Development Command]]|[[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]]|[[1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade]]|[[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|7th Marine Regiment]]|[[1st Battalion 7th Marines|1st Battalion, 7th Marines]]}}\n| battles = {{unbulleted list|[[Gulf War]]|[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]]|[[Iraq War]]|{{*}}[[2003 invasion of Iraq|Invasion of Iraq]]|{{*}}[[First Battle of Fallujah]]|{{*}}[[Second Battle of Fallujah]]}}\n| mawards = {{unbulleted list|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)|[[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]|[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]|[[Legion of Merit]]|[[Bronze Star Medal]] (with [[\"V\" device|Valor]])|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] (3)}}\n}}\n'''James Norman<!-- \"Mad Dog\" is already a listed nickname in the infobox. Don't add it here. --> Mattis''' (born September 8, 1950) is a retired United States Marine general and former government official who served as the 26th [[United States Secretary of Defense]] from January 2017 through January 2019. A retired [[United States Marine Corps]] [[General (United States)|general]], Mattis served in the [[Persian Gulf War]], the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]], and the [[Iraq War]].\n\nMattis was commissioned in the Marine Corps through the [[Naval Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] after graduating from [[Central Washington University]]. A career Marine, he gained a reputation among his peers for \"intellectualism\", and eventually advanced to the rank of general. From 2007 to 2010 he commanded the [[United States Joint Forces Command]] and concurrently served as [[NATO]]'s [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]. He was Commander of [[United States Central Command]] from 2010 to 2013 with Admiral Bob Harward serving as his Deputy Commander. After retiring from the military, he served in several private sector roles, including as a board member of [[Theranos]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/16/17124288/mattis-theranos-board-trump|title=James Mattis is linked to a massive corporate fraud and nobody wants to talk about it|last=Yglesias|first=Matthew|date=March 16, 2018|website=Vox|access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMattis was nominated as Secretary of Defense by President-elect [[Donald Trump]], and confirmed by the Senate on January 20, 2017. As Secretary of Defense, Mattis affirmed the United States' commitment to defending longtime ally [[South Korea]] in the wake of the [[2017\u201318 North Korea crisis|2017 North Korea crisis]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/world/asia/james-mattis-us-korea-thaad.html |title=James Mattis, in South Korea, Tries to Reassure an Ally |newspaper=The New York Times |date=February 2, 2017\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108153812/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/world/asia/james-mattis-us-korea-thaad.html?_r=0 |archive-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"aljazeera.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/warns-north-korea-nuclear-attack-170203034440571.html |title=US warns North Korea against nuclear attack |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204092355/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/warns-north-korea-nuclear-attack-170203034440571.html |archive-date=February 4, 2017 |work=Al Jazeera |date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> An opponent of proposed collaboration with [[China]] and [[Russia]],<ref name=\"baldor\">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mattis-us-ready-collaborate-militarily-russia-45531272|title=Mattis: US not ready to collaborate militarily with Russia |last=Baldor |first=Lolita |date=February 16, 2017 |publisher=ABC News |agency=Associated Press|accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> Mattis stressed what he saw as their \"threat to the American-led world order\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/amp/2386071002|title=Donald Trump disputes departing Defense Secretary Jim Mattis over Russia, China|last=Jackson|first=David|date=December 21, 2018|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Press TV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.presstv.ir/Detail/2017/01/13/506051/James-Mattis-Defense-Department-Donald-Trump-Vladimir-Putin |title=US needs to be ready to confront Russia: Trump's Pentagon pick |publisher= Press TV |date=January 13, 2017}}</ref> Mattis occasionally voiced his disagreement with certain Trump administration policies such as the withdrawal from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran nuclear deal]],<ref name=\"Washington Examiner\">{{cite news |last1=McIntyre |first1=Jamie |title=Mattis: Iran is the biggest threat to Mideast peace |url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mattis-iran-is-the-biggest-threat-to-mideast-peace/article/2589267 |accessdate=December 2, 2016 |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> withdrawals of troops from Syria and Afghanistan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/20/623246756/defense-secretary-mattis-to-retire-in-february-trump-says|title=Defense Secretary Mattis Resigns Amid Syria And Afghanistan Tension|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> and budget cuts hampering the ability to [[climate security|monitor the impacts of climate change]].<ref name=\"Union of Concerned Scientists\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.ucsusa.org/shana-udvardy/secretary-of-defense-james-mattis-the-lone-climate-change-soldier-in-this-administrations-cabinet |title=Secretary of Defense James Mattis: The Lone Climate Change Soldier in this Administration's Cabinet |year=2017 |publisher=Union of Concerned Scientists}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/weather/2018/01/31/climate-change-extreme-weather-military-defense-department-trump-global-warming-wildfires-droughts/1079278001/ |title=Climate change, extreme weather already threaten 50% of U.S. military sites |work=USA Today |date= January 31, 2018}}</ref> On December 20, 2018, after failing to convince Trump to reconsider his decision to withdraw all American troops from Syria, Mattis announced his resignation effective February 28, 2019. Trump, angered by the language of the resignation letter, accelerated the departure date to January 1, stating he had essentially fired him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/02/us/politics/trump-mattis-defense-secretary-generals.html|title=Trump Says Mattis Resignation Was \u2018Essentially\u2019 a Firing, Escalating His New Front Against Military Critics|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=2019-01-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMattis was born on September 8, 1950, in [[Pullman, Washington]].<ref name=SenateNom>{{cite web|title=Nominations before the Senate Armed Services Committee, Second Session, 111th Congress|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-111shrg65070/pdf/CHRG-111shrg65070.pdf|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> He is the son of Lucille (Proulx) Mattis (1922\u20132019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Lucille Mattis Obituary|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tricityherald/obituary.aspx?pid=193576447|work =The Tri-City Herald|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref> and John West Mattis (1915\u20131988),<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About James Mattis|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-01-13/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-james-mattis|accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=James Mattis Fast Facts|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/12/26/us/James-mattis-fast-facts/|publisher=CNN Library|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> a [[United States Merchant Marine|merchant mariner]]. His mother immigrated to the United States from Canada as an infant and had worked in [[Military Intelligence Corps (United States Army)|Army Intelligence]] in [[South Africa]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Reflections with General James Mattis \u2013 Conversations with History|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HOc38ZwEO8s|publisher=University Of California Television|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Mattis's father moved to [[Richland, Washington]], to work at a [[Hanford Site|plant]] supplying [[fissile material]] to the [[Manhattan Project]].<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /> Mattis was raised in a bookish household that did not own a television.<ref name=\"NYBIO\">{{cite news |work=[[The New Yorker]] |title=James Mattis, a Warrior in Washington |date=May 29, 2017 |access-date=May 22, 2017 |url=https://newyorker.com/magazine/2017/05/29/james-mattis-a-warrior-in-washington}}</ref> He graduated from [[Richland High School (Washington)|Richland High School]] in 1968.<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kraemer|first1=Kristin M.|title=Gen. Mattis, Trump's possible defense chief, fulfills Benton County jury duty|url=http://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/article116590898.html|work=Tri-City Herald|date=November 22, 2016}}</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[history]] from [[Central Washington University]] in 1971<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/James-Mattis |title=James Mattis |encyclopedia=Britannica |first=Michael |last=Ray |date=December 2, 2016 |accessdate=December 6, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220233204/https://www.britannica.com/biography/James-Mattis |archivedate=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Baldor>{{cite news|last1=Baldor|first1=Lolita C.|title=Trump to nominate retired Gen. James Mattis to lead Pentagon|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/whitehouse/trump-to-nominate-retired-gen-james-mattis-to-lead-pentagon/2016/12/01/fc8d55a8-b831-11e6-939c-91749443c5e5_story.html|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfcom.mil/|title=Official website|work=United States Joint Forces Command|access-date=September 10, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010202023400/http://www.jfcom.mil/|archive-date=February 2, 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> and a [[Master of Arts]] in international security affairs from the [[National War College]] of [[National Defense University]] in 1994.<ref name=\"Historical Office\">{{cite web|url=http://history.defense.gov/Multimedia/Biographies/Article-View/Article/1059855/james-n-mattis/|title=James N. Mattis \u2013 Donald Trump Administration|work=Office of the Secretary of Defense \u2013 Historical Office}}</ref>\n\n== Military career ==\nMattis enlisted in the [[Marine Corps]] Reserve in 1969.<ref>{{cite AV media | people = Mattis, James | date = September 25, 2013 | title = General James Mattis, \"In the Midst of the Storm: A US Commander's View of the Changing Middle East\" | url =  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vzl8hZWzVpI | access-date = June 2, 2015 | time = 80:10 | publisher = [[Dartmouth College]]}}</ref> He was commissioned a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] on January 1, 1972.<ref name=Reynolds>{{cite book|last=Reynolds|first=Nicholas E.|authorlink=|title=Basrah, Baghdad and Beyond|url=https://archive.org/details/basrahbaghdadbey00reyn/page/4|accessdate=February 20, 2013|year=2005|publisher=|location=|isbn=978-1-59114-717-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/basrahbaghdadbey00reyn/page/4 4\u20135]}}</ref> During his service years, Mattis was considered an \"intellectual\" among the upper ranks.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Ricks|first1=Thomas E.|title=Fiasco|journal=Armed Forces Journal|date=August 1, 2006|url=http://www.armedforcesjournal.com/fiasco/|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Robert H. Scales]], a retired [[United States Army]] [[Major General (United States)|major general]], called him \"one of the most urbane and polished men I have known.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2017/08/james-mattis-no-better-friend-no-worse-enemy/|title=James Mattis: No Better Friend, No Worse Enemy|last=PROSER|first=JIM|date=August 15, 2017|website=Nationalreview|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\nAs a lieutenant, Mattis was assigned as a rifle and weapons [[platoon]] commander in the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]]. As a [[Captain (United States O-3)|captain]], he was assigned as the [[Naval Academy Preparatory School]]'s [[Battalion]] Officer, commanded rifle and weapons companies in the [[1st Marine Regiment (United States)|1st Marine Regiment]], then served at [[Marine Corps Recruiting Command#12th Marine Corps District|Recruiting Station]] [[Portland, Oregon]], as a [[Major (United States)|major]].<ref name=hall />\n\nMattis is a graduate of the U.S. Marine Corps Amphibious Warfare School, [[U.S. Marine Corps Command and Staff College]], and the [[National War College]]. He is noted for his interest in the study of [[military history]] and [[world history]],<ref name=Ricks /><ref name=\"A Marine General at War\" /> with a personal library that once included over 7,000 volumes,<ref name=Kovach /> and a penchant for publishing required reading lists for Marines under his command.<ref name=\"LtGen James Mattis' Reading List\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Small Wars Journal]]|title=LtGen James Mattis' Reading List|url=http://smallwarsjournal.com/blog/ltgen-james-mattis-reading-list|date=June 5, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Ricks, p. 317\">{{cite book| last=Ricks |title=Fiasco: The American Military Adventure in Iraq |page=317}}</ref> He required his Marines to be well-read in the culture and history of regions where they were deployed, and had his Marines deploying to Iraq undergo \"cultural sensitivity training\".<ref name=\"A Marine General at War\" />\n\n=== Persian Gulf War ===\nUpon promotion to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]], Mattis commanded [[1st Battalion, 7th Marines]], one of [[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|Task Force Ripper]]'s assault battalions during the [[Gulf War]].<ref name=\"Lowry\">{{cite news|last1=Lowry|first1=Richard|title=Op-ed: General James N. Mattis \u2013 A Marine for the History Books|url=http://americanmilitarynews.com/2016/12/op-ed-general-james-n-mattis-a-marine-for-the-history-books/|accessdate=March 10, 2017|work=[[American Military News]]|date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== War in Afghanistan ===\n{{further|War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)}}\nAs a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]], Mattis commanded the [[7th Marine Regiment (United States)|7th Marine Regiment]]. He led the [[1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|1st Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] as its commanding officer upon promotion to brigadier general.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Mark|title=Mattis to assume command of I MEF|url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-mattis-to-assume-command-of-i-mef-2006jun02-story.html|accessdate=May 19, 2017|newspaper=San Diego Union-Tribune|date=June 2, 2006}}</ref> It was as a regimental commander that he earned his nickname and call sign, \"CHAOS\", an acronym for \"Colonel Has An Outstanding Solution\", which was initially somewhat tongue-in-cheek.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=McKenzie|title=The origin of Mattis' call sign, 'Chaos'|url=https://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/your-marine-corps/2017/09/21/mattis-explains-the-origin-of-the-call-sign-chaos/|accessdate=October 20, 2017|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|date=September 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the initial planning for the War in Afghanistan, Mattis led [[Task Force 58]] in operations in the southern part of the country beginning in November 2001,<ref>{{cite news |first=Gal Perl|last=Finkel |url=http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/General-Mattis-A-warrior-diplomat-475187 |title=General Mattis: A warrior diplomat |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220162731/http://www.jpost.com/Opinion/General-Mattis-A-warrior-diplomat-475187 |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> becoming the first Marine Corps officer to command a Naval Task Force in combat.<ref name=Reynolds /> According to Mattis, his objective upon arriving in Afghanistan was \"make sure that the enemy didn't feel like they had any safe haven, to destroy their sense of security in southern Afghanistan, to isolate [[Kandahar]] from its lines of communication, and to move against Kandahar.\"<ref name=\"BARZILAI2014\">{{cite book|first=Yaniv |last=Barzilai |title=102 Days of War: How Osama bin Laden, al Qaeda & the Taliban Survived 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsvQAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA45|date=January 31, 2014|publisher=Potomac Books, Inc.|isbn=978-1-61234-534-5|pages=45ff.}}</ref> In December 2001 an airstrike carried out by a [[B-52]] bomber inadvertently targeted a position held by U.S. [[special operations]] troops and Afghan militiamen in [[Urozgan Province]]. Numerous men were wounded in the incident, but Mattis repeatedly refused to dispatch helicopters from the nearby [[Camp Rhino]] to recover them, citing operational safety concerns. Instead an Air Force helicopter flew from [[Uzbekistan]] to ferry the men to the [[U.S. Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] base where helicopters sat readily available but unauthorized to fly. Captain [[Jason Amerine]] blamed the delay caused by Mattis's refusal to order a rescue operation for the deaths of several men. Amerine wrote, \"Every element in Afghanistan tried to help us except the closest friendly unit, commanded by Mattis,\" though he also wrote that \"none of that was assessed properly because the [5th Special Forces Group] chose not to call for a formal investigation\".<ref name=\"Tritten 2016\">{{cite web |last=Tritten |first=Travis J. |title=Retired Green Beret says Mattis left 'my men to die' in Afghanistan |website=Stars and Stripes |date=December 2, 2016 |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/retired-green-beret-says-mattis-left-my-men-to-die-in-afghanistan-1.442367 |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Vladimirov 2016\">{{cite web |last=Vladimirov |first=Nikita |title=Former Special Forces officer: Mattis 'betrayed his duty to us' |work=The Hill |date=December 2, 2016 |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/308527-former-special-forces-officer-blasts-trump-defense-secretary |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref> This episode was used against Mattis when he was nominated for Defense Secretary in 2016.<ref name=\"Meek Ferran 2016\">{{cite web |last=Meek |first=James Gordon |last2=Ferran |first2=Lee |title=Men Left 'to Die': Gen. James Mattis' Controversial Wartime Decision |publisher=ABC News |date=December 6, 2016 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/men-left-die-gen-james-mattis-controversial-wartime/story?id=44018222 |access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile serving in Afghanistan as a [[brigadier general]], Mattis was known{{by whom|date=January 2019}} as an officer who engaged his men with \"real leadership.\"{{clarify|date=January 2019}} He also was quoted as saying \"be polite, be courteous, and have a plan to kill everyone you meet.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2010/07/16-most-hair-raising-general-mattis-quotes/340553/|title=16 Most Hair-Raising General Mattis Quotes|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=July 9, 2010|work=The Atlantic|access-date=September 5, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> A young Marine officer, [[Nathaniel Fick]], said he witnessed Mattis in a [[Defensive fighting position|fighting hole]] talking with a sergeant and lance corporal: \"No one would have questioned Mattis if he'd slept eight hours each night in a private room, to be woken each morning by an aide who ironed his uniforms and heated his [[Meal, Ready-to-Eat|MREs]]. But there he was, in the middle of a freezing night, out on the lines with his Marines.\"<ref name=RicksG>{{cite book|author-link=Thomas E. Ricks (journalist) |first=Thomas E.|last= Ricks|title=The Generals: American Military Command from World War II to Today|date=2012|page=405|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York|isbn=978-1-59420-404-3}}</ref>\n\n=== Iraq War ===\n[[File:Genmattisltr.jpg|thumb|200px|Letter written by Mattis on the eve of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], addressed to members of the 1st Marine Division]]\nAs a [[Major general (United States)|major general]], Mattis commanded the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=Ricks>{{cite book|title=[[Fiasco (book)|Fiasco: The American Military Adventure in Iraq]]|author-link=Thomas E. Ricks (journalist) |first=Thomas E.|last= Ricks|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York|year=2006|page=313}}</ref> Mattis played key roles in combat operations in [[Fallujah]], including negotiation with the insurgent command inside the city during [[First Battle of Fallujah|Operation Vigilant Resolve]] in April 2004, as well as participation in planning of the subsequent [[Second Battle of Fallujah|Operation Phantom Fury]] in November.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szoldra|first1=Paul|title=19 unforgettable quotes from legendary Marine Gen. James 'Mad Dog' Mattis|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/general-mattiss-best-quotes-2016-11/#i-dont-lose-any-sleep-at-night-over-the-potential-for-failure-i-cannot-even-spell-the-word-7|accessdate=May 19, 2017|work=Business Insider|date=December 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2004 Mattis ordered the 3&nbsp;a.m. bombing of what he alleged was a suspected enemy [[safe house]] near the Syrian border, but was in fact [[Mukaradeeb_wedding_party_massacre|a wedding party]] and resulted in the deaths of 42 civilians, including 11 women and 14 children. Mattis said it had taken him 30 seconds to decide whether to bomb the location. Describing the wedding as implausible, he said, \"How many people go to the middle of the desert to hold a wedding {{Convert|80|mi|abbr=out}} from the nearest civilization? These were more than two dozen military-age males. Let's not be naive.\"<ref>{{Cite book|first=Bing|last=West|year=2008|title=The Strongest Tribe: War, Politics, and the Endgame in Iraq|location=New York, NY|publisher=[[Random House]]|isbn=978-1-4000-6701-5|p=[https://archive.org/details/strongesttribewa00west/page/245 245]|url=https://archive.org/details/strongesttribewa00west/page/245}}</ref> The occurrence of a wedding was disputed by military officials, but the [[Associated Press]] obtained video footage showing a wedding party and a video the next day showed musical instruments and party decoration among the remains.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2004/05/24/iraq-wedding-party-video-backs-survivors-claims.html|title=Iraq Wedding-Party Video Backs Survivors' Claims|date=May 24, 2004|newspaper=Fox News|access-date=February 10, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204165706/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2004/05/24/iraq-wedding-party-video-backs-survivors-claims.html|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> When asked by the press about footage on Arabic television of a child's body being lowered into a grave, he replied: \"I have not seen the pictures but bad things happen in wars. I don't have to apologise for the conduct of my men.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/may/21/iraq.rorymccarthy|title='US soldiers started to shoot us, one by one'|date=20 May 2004|website=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a Department of Defense survey that showed only 55% of U.S. soldiers and 40% of Marines would report a colleague for abusing civilians, Mattis told Marines in May 2007 that \"whenever you show anger or disgust toward civilians, it's a victory for [[al-Qaeda]] and other insurgents.\" Believing that a need for restraint in war is key to defeating an insurgency, he added: \"every time you wave at an Iraqi civilian, al-Qaeda rolls over in its grave.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=General Urges Marines To Add A Friendly Wave To Their Arsenal|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/17/world/fg-force17|last=Perry|first=Tony|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 17, 2007|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMattis popularized the 1st Marine Division's motto \"no better friend, no worse enemy\", a paraphrase of the epitaph the [[Roman dictator]] [[Sulla|Lucius Cornelius Sulla]] wrote for himself,<ref name=Durant>{{cite book |last=Durant |first=Will |authorlink=Will Durant|title=Heroes of History: A Brief History of Civilization from Ancient Times to the Dawn of the Modern Age |url=https://archive.org/details/heroesofhistoryb00dura |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |date=2001 |page=[https://archive.org/details/heroesofhistoryb00dura/page/131 131] |isbn=0-7432-2910-X}}</ref> in his open letter to all men within the division for their return to Iraq. This phrase later became widely publicized during the investigation into the conduct of Lieutenant [[Ilario Pantano]], a platoon commander serving under Mattis.<ref name=StarNewsOnline051228>{{cite news|url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20051228/NEWS/51227016&SearchID=73247366207350|title=Top 10 Stories of 2005: Pantano, roads, Olchowski are 10\u20137|date=December 28, 2005|work=Star News Online|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=Time050228>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1032357-1,00.html|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|title=Did He Go Too Far?|date=February 28, 2005|author=Quinn-Judge, Paul|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=Msnbc060426>{{cite news|date=April 26, 2005|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7250029|title=Marine charged with murders of Iraqis: Lieutenant claims self-defense in shooting of detainees|publisher=[[NBC News]]|author=Phillips, Stone|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=StarsAndStripes0511116>{{cite news|url=http://stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=33048|title=Marine acquitted in Iraqi shootings will publish a book|author=Jeff Schogol|work=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|date=November 16, 2005|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref><ref name=NorthCountyTimes060701>{{cite news|url=http://www.nctimes.com/articles/2006/07/02/news/top_stories/22_22_057_1_06.txt|title=Pantano case has parallels to Hamdania incident|author=Walker, Mark|date=July 1, 2006|work=[[North County Times]]|accessdate=January 24, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAs his division prepared to ship out, Mattis called in \"experts on the Middle East\" for \"cultural sensitivity training\". He constantly toured the battlefield to tell stories of Marines who were able to show \"discretion in moments of high pressure\". As an apparent example, he encouraged his Marines to grow moustaches to look more like the people they were working with.<ref name=\"A Marine General at War\">{{cite news|url-status=live |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/risk/2010/04/a_marine_general_at_war.html |title=A Marine General at War |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111121158/http://www.slate.com/articles/life/risk/2010/04/a_marine_general_at_war.html |archive-date=January 11, 2017 |first=John |last=Dickerson |work=Slate |date=April 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe also was noted for a willingness to remove senior leaders under his command at a time when the U.S. military seemed unable or unwilling to relieve underperforming or incompetent officers. During the division's push to Baghdad, Mattis relieved Colonel Joe D. Dowdy, commander of [[1st Marine Regiment (United States)|Regimental Combat Team-1]]. It was such a rare occurrence in the modern military that it made the front page of newspapers. Despite this, Mattis declined to comment on the matter publicly other than to say that the practice of officer relief remains alive, or at least \"we are doing it in the Marines.\"<ref name=RicksG /> Later interviews of Dowdy's officers and men revealed that \"the colonel was doomed partly by an age-old wartime tension: Men versus mission\u2014in which he favored his men\", while Mattis insisted on execution of the mission to seize Baghdad swiftly.<ref name=WSJ_Cooper>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108111980285073875|title=How a Marine Lost His Command In Race to Baghdad|author=Cooper, Christopher|date=April 5, 2004|work=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Combat Development Command ===\nAfter being promoted to [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]], Mattis took command of [[Marine Corps Combat Development Command]]. On February 1, 2005, speaking at a forum in [[San Diego]], he said \"You go into Afghanistan, you got guys who slap women around for five years because they didn't wear a veil. You know, guys like that ain't got no manhood left anyway. So it's a hell of a lot of fun to shoot them. Actually, it's a lot of fun to fight. You know, it's a hell of a hoot. It's fun to shoot some people. I'll be right upfront with you, I like brawling.\" Mattis's remarks sparked controversy; General [[Michael Hagee]], [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]], issued a statement suggesting Mattis should have chosen his words more carefully but would not be disciplined.<ref name=AmericanSpectator>{{cite web |url=https://spectator.org/48978_breaking-warrior-code/ |title=Breaking the Warrior Code |author= Guardiano, John R. |work=[[The American Spectator]] |date=February 11, 2005 |accessdate=January 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== U.S. Joint Forces Command ===\n[[File:From left, Vice President Joe Biden, Secretary of Defense Robert M. Gates, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Navy Adm. Mike Mullen and U.S. Marine Corps Gen. Gen. James Mattis, the commander of U.S. Central 100901-N-TT977-147.jpg|thumb|left|Vice President [[Joe Biden]], Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]], Admiral [[Mike Mullen]] and General Mattis in Baghdad, Iraq]]\n\n[[The Pentagon]] announced on May 31, 2006, that Mattis had been chosen to take command of the [[I Marine Expeditionary Force]], based out of [[Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton]].<ref name = MCTimes>{{cite news|first=Christian |last=Lowe|title=Popular commander to lead I MEF|work=[[Marine Corps Times]]|page=24|date=June 12, 2006}}</ref> On September 11, 2007, Secretary of Defense [[Robert Gates]] announced that President [[George W. Bush]] had nominated Mattis for appointment to the rank of general to command [[United States Joint Forces Command|U.S. Joint Forces Command]] in [[Norfolk, Virginia]]. NATO agreed to appoint Mattis as [[Allied Command Transformation|Supreme Allied Commander Transformation]]. On September 28, 2007, the [[United States Senate]] confirmed Mattis's nomination, and he relinquished command of the I MEF on November 5, 2007, to Lieutenant General Samuel Helland.<ref name=\"hall\">{{cite web|title=Gen James N. Mattis|url=http://www.militaryhallofhonor.com/honoree-record.php?id=405|publisher=Military Hall of Honor|accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMattis was promoted to four-star general and took control of JFCOM/[[Allied Command Transformation|SACT]] on November 9, 2007. He transferred the job of SACT to General [[St\u00e9phane Abrial]] of France on September 9, 2009, but continued in command of JFCOM.<ref name=\"NATOawards\" />\n\n=== U.S. Central Command ===\nIn early 2010 Mattis was reported to be on the list of generals being considered to replace [[James T. Conway]] as the Commandant of the U.S. Marine Corps.<ref name=\"CMC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/06/ap_CMC_062110/|title=Gates announces nomination of Amos for CMC|last=Gearan|first=Anne|date=June 22, 2010|agency=Associated Press|work=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322203931/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/06/ap_CMC_062110/ |archivedate=March 22, 2012}}</ref> In July he was recommended by [[United States Secretary of Defense|Defense Secretary]] [[Robert Gates]] for nomination to replace [[David Petraeus]] as commander of [[United States Central Command]] (CENTCOM),<ref name=SenateNom /><ref name=\"MCT CENTCOM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/military_mattis_centcom_070810w/|title=Pentagon picks Mattis to take over CENTCOM|last=Cavallaro|first=Gina|date=July 8, 2010|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 8, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712031949/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/military_mattis_centcom_070810w/|archivedate=July 12, 2010}}</ref> and formally nominated by President Obama on July 21.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/marine_mattis_centcom_072110w/|title=Obama backs Mattis nomination for CENTCOM|date=July 22, 2010|newspaper=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=July 23, 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117234339/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/07/marine_mattis_centcom_072110w/|archivedate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Mattis had planned to retire before the appointment.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2012/04/centcom-commander-general-mad-dog-mattis-set-to-retire/|title=CENTCOM Commander \u2018Mad Dog\u2019 General James Mattis Set To Retire|first=Dark|last=Laughter|date=April 27, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis confirmation by the [[United States Senate|Senate]] marked the first time Marines had held billets as commander and deputy commander of a [[unified combatant command]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fayobserver.com/articles/2010/08/06/1019648|title=Petraeus' replacement at Central Command confirmed|date=August 6, 2010|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Fayetteville Observer]]|accessdate=August 6, 2010}}</ref> He took command at a ceremony at [[MacDill Air Force Base]] on August 11.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2010/08/11/mattis-takes-central-command-vows-work-mideast-allies-afghanistan-iraq/|title=Mattis takes over Central Command, vows to work with Mideast allies in Afghanistan, Iraq|date=August 11, 2010|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tampabay.com/news/article1114800.ece|title=Mattis takes over as CentCom chief|last=Mitchell|first=Robbyn|date=August 12, 2010|newspaper=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|page=1|accessdate=August 12, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012171654/http://www.tampabay.com/news/article1114800.ece|archivedate=October 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centcom.mil/news/mattis-assumes-command-of-centcom|title=Mattis assumes command of CENTCOM|date=August 11, 2010|publisher=U.S. Central Command|accessdate=August 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs head of Central Command, Mattis oversaw the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan and was responsible for a region that includes [[Syria]], Iran, and Yemen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/04/11/syria-iran-mattis-central-command-chief-interview/2069935/|title=Mattis interview: Syria would fall without Iran's help|date=April 12, 2013|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=September 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011204715/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/04/11/syria-iran-mattis-central-command-chief-interview/2069935/|archive-date=October 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He lobbied the Obama administration for a more aggressive response to Iran, including more covert operations and disruption of Iranian arms shipments to Syria and [[Yemen]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Why the chaos in Yemen could force Obama to take a harder line with Iran |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-sectarian-chaos-spreads-obamas-middle-east-policy-buckles/2015/03/28/f8cc8f56-d570-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html |work=Washington Post |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |date=March 28, 2015|first1=Greg |last1= Jaffe |first2=Missy |last2=Ryan}}</ref> According to [[Leon Panetta]], the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] did not place much trust in Mattis because he was perceived as too eager for a military confrontation with [[Iran\u2013United States relations|Iran]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Panetta|first=Leon|title=Worthy Fights: A Memoir of Leadership in War and Peace|pp=Kindle Locations 6368\u20136370|publisher=[[Penguin Group]]|edition=Kindle}}</ref> Panetta later said Mattis lacked \"the maturity to look at all of the options that a president should look at in order to make the right decisions\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/as-a-general-mattis-urged-action-against-iran-as-a-defense-secretary-he-may-be-a-voice-of-caution/2017/01/08/5a196ade-d391-11e6-a783-cd3fa950f2fd_story.html |work=Washington Post |accessdate=December 29, 2018 |title=As a general, Mattis urged action against Iran. As a defense secretary, he may be a voice of caution.|date=January 8, 2017 |first1=Greg |last1=Jaffe |first2=Adam |last2=Entous}}</ref>\n\nMattis announced his retirement from the Marine Corps in April 2012, effective in a matter of months.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Eight months later, the Defense Department nominated General [[Lloyd Austin]] to succeed Mattis, who retired in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/austin-will-be-nominated-to-lead-us-central-command-1.199642|title=Austin will be nominated to lead US Central Command|website=Stars and Stripes|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=FWA /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defense.gov/About/Biographies/Biography-View/Article/1055835/james-mattis|title=James Mattis|publisher=United States Department of Defense|quote=Following his retirement from the U.S. Marine Corps in 2013, Secretary Mattis served as the Davies Family Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, specializing in the study of leadership, national security, strategy, innovation, and the effective use of military force.}}</ref>\n\n== Civilian career ==\n[[File:James Mattis official Transition portrait.jpg|thumb|180px|right|Mattis in 2016]]\nAfter retiring from the military, Mattis worked for FWA Consultants and served as a member of the [[General Dynamics]] Board of Directors.<ref name=FWA>{{cite web|url=http://fwaconsultants.homestead.com/MattisBio.html|title=About General James Mattis|publisher=FWA Consultants|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> Between 2013 to 2017, while on the board of [[General Dynamics]], Mattis made more than $900,000 in compensation, including company stock.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibtimes.com/political-capital/donald-trump-pentagon-pick-mattis-made-nearly-1000000-board-defense-contractor|title=Donald Trump Pentagon Pick Mattis Made Nearly $1,000,000 On Board Of Defense Contractor|last=Asher-Schapiro|first=Avi|date=2016-12-02|website=International Business Times|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> In August 2013, he was appointed an Annenberg Distinguished Visiting Fellow at the [[Hoover Institution]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoover.org/profiles/james-mattis|title=General James Mattis, Annenberg Distinguished Visiting Fellow|publisher=Hoover Institute|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref> and in 2016 he was named the Davies Family Distinguished Visiting Fellow.<ref>{{cite web|title=General James Mattis|url=http://www.hoover.org/profiles/james-mattis|publisher=Hoover Institution|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Mattis joined the [[advisory board]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mattis|first1=James|title=Why I'm Joining Spirit of America|url=https://spiritofamerica.org/blog/im-joining-spirit-america|publisher=Spirit of America|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> of [[Spirit of America (charity)|Spirit of America]], a [[501(c)(3) organization|501(c)(3) nonprofit organization]] that provides assistance to support the safety and success of American service personnel and the local people they seek to help.\n\nHe is co-editor of the book ''Warriors & Citizens: American Views of Our Military'', published in August 2016.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Mattis|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Schake|editor2-first=Kori|editor2link=Kori Schake|title=Warriors and Citizens: American Views of Our Military|date=August 2016|publisher=[[Hoover Institution]]|location=Stanford, California|isbn=978-0-8179-1934-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1gpmDAAAQBAJ|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2013 to January 2017, Mattis was a board member of [[Theranos]], a [[Health technology in the United States|health technology]] company that claimed to have devised revolutionary [[blood test]]s using very small amounts of blood.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Carreyrou|title=Bad Blood: Secrets and Lies in a Silicon Valley Startup|date=May 21, 2018|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-5247-3166-3}}{{page needed|date=December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Levine|first1=Matt|title=The Blood Unicorn Theranos Was Just a Fairy Tale|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-03-14/theranos-misled-investors-and-consumers-who-used-its-blood-test|accessdate=March 14, 2018|work=Bloomberg View|date=March 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Weaver|first1=Christopher|title=Trump Defense Nominee James Mattis Resigns From Theranos Board|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-defense-nominee-james-mattis-resigns-from-theranos-board-1483649696|accessdate=January 28, 2017|work=Wall Street Journal|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/06/12/theranos-board-directors/|title=A singular board at Theranos|date=June 12, 2014|work=Fortune|accessdate=October 12, 2015}}</ref> Previously, in mid-2012, a Department of Defense official evaluating Theranos's blood-testing technology for the military initiated a formal inquiry with the [[Food and Drug Administration]] about the company's intent to distribute its tests without FDA clearance. In August 2012 Theranos CEO [[Elizabeth Holmes]] asked Mattis, who had expressed interest in testing Theranos's technology in combat areas, to help. Within hours, Mattis forwarded his email exchange with Holmes to military officials, asking \"how do we overcome this new obstacle\". In July 2013 the Department of Defense gave Mattis permission to join Theranos's board provided he did not represent Theranos with regard to the blood-testing device and its potential acquisition by the Departments of the Navy or Defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2015/12/02/internal-emails-reveal-concerns-about-theranoss-fda-compliance-date-back-years/ |title=E-mails reveal concerns about Theranos's FDA compliance date back years|date=December 2, 2015|first =Carolyn Y.|last= Johnson|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Mattis's book ''Call Sign Chaos: Learning to Lead'' was published.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/30/books/review/call-sign-chaos-jim-mattis-and-bing-west.html|title=Jim Mattis Tells His Life Story|first=Risa|last=Brooks|date=August 30, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> It is an autobiography as well as an argument in favor of an [[Internationalism (politics)|internationalist]] foreign policy.<ref>Goldberg, Jeffrey.  [https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/10/james-mattis-trump/596665/ \"Why Did James Mattis Resign ....\"] ''The Atlantic''.  October 2019.  29 August 2019.</ref> On August 7, 2019, Mattis was re-elected to the board of [[General Dynamics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gd.com/Articles/2019/08/07/general-dynamics-elects-jim-mattis-to-board-of-directors|title=General Dynamics Elects Jim Mattis to Board of Directors|website=www.gd.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\n== Secretary of Defense (2017\u20132019) ==\n\n=== Nomination and confirmation ===\n[[File:President Donald J. Trump departs from the Pentagon alongside Secretary of Defense James Mattis on January 27, 2017, in Washington, D.C. (32181624010).jpg|thumb|right|Mattis with President [[Donald Trump|Trump]] and Vice President [[Mike Pence|Pence]]]]\nThen-President-elect [[Donald Trump]] met with Mattis for a little over one hour in [[Bedminster, New Jersey]], on November 20, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/19/politics/donald-trump-james-mattis-defense-secretary/index.html|title=Trump: 'Mad Dog' Mattis is a 'very impressive' candidate for defense secretary|date=November 20, 2016|author=Phil Mattingly|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> He later wrote on [[Twitter]], \"General James 'Mad Dog' Mattis, who is being considered for Secretary of Defense, was very impressive yesterday. A true General's General!\"<ref>{{cite tweet  |user=realDonaldTrump |number=800332639844659201|title=General James \"Mad Dog\" Mattis, who is being considered for Secretary of Defense, was very impressive yesterday. A true General's General! |date=November 11, 2016|first=Donald J.|last=Trump |accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> On December 1, 2016, Trump announced at a rally in Cincinnati that he would nominate Mattis for [[United States Secretary of Defense]].<ref name=wp20161201>{{cite news|last=Lamothe |first=Dan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-has-chosen-retired-marine-gen-james-mattis-for-secretary-of-defense/2016/12/01/6c6b3b74-aff9-11e6-be1c-8cec35b1ad25_story.html |title=Trump has chosen retired Marine Gen. James Mattis for secretary of defense |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=December 1, 2016 |accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs Mattis retired from the military in 2013, his nomination required a waiver of the [[National Security Act of 1947]], which requires a seven-year waiting period before retired military personnel can assume the role of Secretary of Defense.<ref name=wp20161201 /> Mattis was the second Secretary of Defense to receive such a waiver, following [[George Marshall]].<ref name=wp20161201 /> The waiver for Mattis passed 81\u201317 in the Senate, and 268\u2013151 in the House. Mattis was subsequently confirmed as Secretary of Defense by a vote of 98\u20131 in the United States Senate on January 20, 2017.<ref name=\"WaPo confirmation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/01/20/senate-confirms-retired-gen-james-mattis-as-defense-secretary-breaking-with-decades-of-precedent/ |title=Senate confirms retired Gen. James Mattis as defense secretary, breaking with decades of precedent |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 20, 2017}}</ref> Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] was the sole \"no\" vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-confirms-james-mattis-as-defense-secretary-1484952996?mod=e2tw|title=Senate Confirms James Mattis as Defense Secretary |last1=Peterson |first1=Kristina |last2=Hughes |first2=Siobhan  |date=January 20, 2017 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> stating that she was opposed to the waiver on principle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/kirsten-gillibrand-mattis-waiver-232099 |title=Gillibrand says she won't vote for Mattis waiver |last=Schor |first=Elana |date=January 20, 2017 |work=[[Politico]] |quote=While I deeply respect General Mattis's service, I will oppose a waiver. Civilian control of our military is a fundamental principle of American democracy, and I will not vote for an exception to this rule.|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n[[File:JamesN.Mattis.Nurettin Canikli.JPG|thumb|Mattis and Turkish Defense Minister [[Nurettin Canikli]] at NATO headquarters in Brussels, February 2018]]\nIn a January 2017 phone call with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s deputy crown prince [[Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud|Mohammed bin Salman]], Mattis \"reaffirmed the importance of the [[Saudi Arabia\u2013United States relations|U.S.\u2013Saudi Arabia strategic relationship]]\".<ref>{{cite document |url=https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1066487/readout-of-secretary-mattis-call-with-kingdom-of-saudi-arabias-deputy-crown-pri |title=Readout of Secretary Mattis' Call with Kingdom of Saudi Arabia's Deputy Crown Prince and Minister of Defense Mohammed bin Salman |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201043709/https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1066487/readout-of-secretary-mattis-call-with-kingdom-of-saudi-arabias-deputy-crown-pri |archive-date=February 1, 2017 |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |date=January 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor his first official trip abroad, Mattis began a two-day visit with longtime U.S. ally [[South Korea]] on February 2, 2017.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" /> He warned [[North Korea]] that \"any attack on the United States, or our allies, will be defeated\", and any use of nuclear weapons would be met with an \"effective and overwhelming\" response from the United States.<ref name=\"aljazeera.com\" /> During a press conference in [[London]] on March 31, 2017, with his UK counterpart [[Secretary of State for Defence]] [[Michael Fallon]], Mattis said North Korea was behaving \"in a very reckless manner\" and must be stopped.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/defense-sec-james-mattis-north-korea-has-got-be-stopped-n740966|title=Defense Sec. James Mattis: North Korea 'Has Got to Be Stopped'|date=March 31, 2017|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=December 28, 2018 |first1=Alexander |last1=Smith |first2=Gabe|last2= Joselow }}</ref> During a Pentagon news conference on May 26, Mattis reported the U.S. was working with the UN, China, Japan, and South Korea to avoid \"a military solution\" with North Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-military-solution-north-korea-would-be-tragic-2017-5|title=James Mattis says a military solution in North Korea will 'be tragic on an unbelievable scale'|date=May 26, 2017|work=Business Insider}}</ref> On June 3 Mattis said the United States regarded North Korea as \"clear and present danger\" during a speech at the international security conference in [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/defense-secretary-mattis-turns-up-heat-on-north-korea-and-china/|title=Defense Secretary Mattis turns up heat on North Korea and China|date=June 3, 2017|publisher=CBS News|agency=Reuters |first1=Phil |last1=Stewart |first2=David|last2= Brunnstrom }}</ref> In a June 12 written statement to the [[House Armed Services Committee]] Mattis said North Korea was the \"most urgent and dangerous threat to peace and security\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-northkorea-idUSKBN19407I|title=North Korea 'most urgent' threat to security: Mattis|first1=Idrees|last1=Ali |first2=Mike|last2=Stone|work=Reuters|date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> On June 15 Mattis said the U.S. would win a war against North Korea, but \"at great cost\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-north-korea-war-we-will-win-2017-6|title=Defense Secretary Mattis explains what war with North Korea would look like|date=June 16, 2017|first=Alex|last=Lockie|work=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2017, during questioning from the U.S. Senate, Mattis affirmed his support for U.S. troops remaining in Iraq after the [[Battle of Mosul (2016\u20132017)|Battle of Mosul]] was concluded.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/articles/mattis-troops-iraq-years-after-isis |title=Mattis: Expect U.S. troops in Iraq even after ISIS falls|date=March 22, 2017|work=Military Times|first=Leo|last=Shane III}}</ref> Mattis responded to critics who suggested the Trump administration had loosened the [[rules of engagement]] for the [[Operation Inherent Resolve|U.S. military in Iraq]] after U.S.-led coalition [[2017 Mosul airstrike|airstrikes in Mosul]] killed civilians,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-mosul-usa-idUSKBN16Y2BA |title=After civilians killed in Mosul, Pentagon denies loosening rules |date=March 27, 2017|work=Reuters}}</ref> saying, \"We go out of our way to always do everything humanly possible to reduce the loss of life or injury among innocent people.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/04/11/civilian-casualties-are-up-and-congress-is-awol/|title=Civilian casualties are up and Congress is AWOL |date=April 11, 2017 |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |accessdate= December 31, 2018 |first=Micah |last= Zenko}}</ref> According to ''Airwars'', the U.S.-led coalition killed as many as 6,000 civilians in Iraq and Syria in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-deaths-tripled-in-us-led-campaign-during-2017-watchdog-alleges/2018/01/18/ccfae298-fc6d-11e7-a46b-a3614530bd87_story.html |title=Civilian deaths tripled in U.S.-led campaign against ISIS in 2017, watchdog alleges |url-status=live |first=Missy |last=Ryan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430183007/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/civilian-deaths-tripled-in-us-led-campaign-during-2017-watchdog-alleges/2018/01/18/ccfae298-fc6d-11e7-a46b-a3614530bd87_story.html |archive-date=April 30, 2018 |work=The Washington Post |date=January 18, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:SD visits Australia 170605-D-GY869-1426 (34320481913).jpg|thumb|Mattis and [[Marise Payne]] inspecting the [[Australia's Federation Guard]] in [[Sydney]].]]\nOn April 5, 2017, Mattis called the [[Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]] \"a heinous act,\" and said it would be treated accordingly.<ref>{{cite news|first=Carlos |last=Mu\u00f1oz |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/apr/5/mattis-condemns-heinous-chemical-attack-syria/|title=Defense Secretary Mattis condemns 'heinous' chemical attack in Syria, DoD mulls response|date=April 5, 2017|work=Washington Times}}</ref> On April 10 Mattis warned the Syrian government against using [[Chemical warfare|chemical weapons]] again.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement by Secretary of Defense James Mattis on the U.S. Military Response to the Syrian Government's Use of Chemical Weapons|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/News-Releases/News-Release-View/Article/1146758/statement-by-secretary-of-defense-James-mattis-on-the-us-military-response-to-the/|publisher=United States Department of Defense|date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The following day, Mattis gave his first Pentagon news conference since becoming Secretary of Defense, saying [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]'s defeat remained \"our priority,\" and the Syrian government would pay a \"very, very stiff price\" for further usage of chemical weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/mattis-syria-policy-defeat-isis-237122|title=Mattis: U.S. Syria policy is still to defeat ISIS|first=Jacqueline|last=Klimas|date=April 11, 2017|work=Politico}}</ref> On April 21 Mattis said Syria still had chemical weapons and was in violation of United Nations Security Council resolutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/us-defense-secy-mattis-syria-chemical-weapons-46931091|title=US Defense Sec'y Mattis: Syria still has chemical weapons|first=Robert|last=Burns|publisher=ABC News|date=April 21, 2017|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170421221230/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/us-defense-secy-mattis-syria-chemical-weapons-46931091|archivedate=April 21, 2017}}</ref> According to investigative journalist [[Bob Woodward]], Trump ordered Mattis to assassinate Assad, but Mattis refused.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump wanted Syria's Assad assassinated, Bob Woodward claims in extraordinary new book |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-bob-woodward-fear-book-syria-assad-kill-claims-a8523176.html |work=Independent |date=April 9, 2018}}</ref> On May 8 Mattis told reporters details of the proposed Syrian safe zones were \"all in process right now\" and the United States was involved with configuring them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/332366-mattis-questions-unanswered-on-syria-cease-fire-plan|title=Mattis: Questions unanswered on Syria cease-fire plan|first=Ellen|last=Mitchell|date=May 8, 2017|work=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nMattis voiced support for a [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|Saudi Arabian-led military campaign]] against [[Yemen]]'s [[Zaidiyyah|Shiite]] rebels.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/03/26/pentagon-weighs-more-support-for-saudi-led-war-in-yemen/ |title=Pentagon Weighs More Support for Saudi-led War in Yemen |date=March 26, 2017|work=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref> He asked Trump to remove restrictions on U.S. military support for Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-administration-weighs-deeper-involvement-in-yemen-war/2017/03/26/b81eecd8-0e49-11e7-9d5a-a83e627dc120_story.html |title=Trump administration weighs deeper involvement in Yemen war |date=March 26, 2017|work=The Washington Post|first1=Karen |last1=DeYoung |first2=Missy|last2=Ryan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, 2017, one week after the [[2017 Nangarhar airstrike|Nangarhar airstrike]], Mattis told reporters that the U.S. would not conduct a damage assessment \"in terms of the number of people killed\" in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/20/James-mattis-mother-of-all-bombs-afghanistan-damage-237413|title=Mattis: U.S. won't dig into 'mother of all bombs' damage in Afghanistan|first=Jacqueline|last=Klimas|date=April 20, 2017|work=Politico}}</ref> Mattis traveled to Afghanistan days later and met with government officials, explaining that the purpose of the trip was to allow him to state his recommendations for U.S. strategy in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/24/politics/mattis-afghanistan-visit/ |title=US Defense Secretary Mattis visits Afghanistan|first1=Susannah|last1=Cullinane|first2=Ryan|last2=Browne |publisher=CNN|date=March 27, 2017}}</ref> On June 13, Mattis said U.S. forces were \"not winning\" in Afghanistan and the administration would develop a new strategy by \"mid-July\" while speaking to the [[United States Senate Committee on Armed Services]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/06/13/James-mattis-not-winning-afghanistan-239488|title=Mattis: 'We are not winning in Afghanistan'|first=Connor|last=O'Brien|date=June 13, 2017|publisher=Politico}}</ref> On June 27 Mattis told reporters that he was creating a conflict-ending strategy for Afghanistan that would also \"remove the danger to the Afghan people and to us and to all the nations that have been attacked by terrorist groups out of that region\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pjmedia.com/news-and-politics/2017/06/27/mattis-crafting-strategy-to-remove-the-danger-to-the-afghan-people-and-to-us/|title=Mattis Crafting Strategy to 'Remove the Danger to the Afghan People and to Us'|first=Bridget|last=Johnson|publisher=PJMedia.com |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> On June 29 Mattis said the Obama administration \"may have pulled our troops out too rapidly\" and that he intended to submit a new Afghanistan strategy to Trump upon his return to Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/29/mattis-says-us-may-have-pulled-our-troops-out-too-rapidly-in-afghanistan.html|title=Mattis says US 'may have pulled our troops out too rapidly' in Afghanistan|date=June 29, 2017|publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\nThe United States has been openly arming the [[Syrian Democratic Forces|Syrian Kurdish]] fighters in the war against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] since May 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/turkey-joins-syria-chaos-us-tries-find-someone-hold-peace-kurds-786828 |title=Turkish Forces Bomb Key U.S. Ally In Fight Against ISIS In Syria |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215025525/http://www.newsweek.com/turkey-joins-syria-chaos-us-tries-find-someone-hold-peace-kurds-786828 |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=January 22, 2018 |first=Zachary |last=Fryer-Biggs}}</ref> Following the start of the [[Operation Olive Branch|Turkish invasion of northern Syria]] aimed at ousting U.S.-backed Syrian Kurds from the enclave of [[Afrin, Syria|Afrin]], Mattis said in January 2018: \"Turkey is a NATO ally. It's the only NATO country with an active insurgency inside its borders. And Turkey has legitimate security concerns.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-legitimate-security-concerns-mattis-126090 |title= Turkey has legitimate security concerns: Mattis |agency=Andalou Agency |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215083638/http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/turkey-has-legitimate-security-concerns-mattis-126090 |archive-date=February 15, 2018 |work= [[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> Turkish Deputy Prime Minister [[Bekir Bozda\u011f]] urged the United States to halt its support for Kurdish [[People's Protection Units|YPG]] fighters, saying: \"Those who support the terrorist organization will become a target in this battle.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/01/turkey-stop-ypg-support-face-confrontation-180125182540759.html|title=Turkey to US: Stop YPG support or face 'confrontation' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213150333/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/01/turkey-stop-ypg-support-face-confrontation-180125182540759.html |archive-date=February 13, 2018 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=January 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Resignation-Letter-From-Secretary-James-N-Mattis.pdf|thumb|Resignation letter from Secretary James Mattis]]\nIn November 2018 the [[CIA]] assessed with \"high confidence\" that [[Saudi Arabia]]'s Crown Prince [[Mohammad bin Salman]] ordered the assassination of [[The Washington Post|''Washington Post'']] columnist [[Jamal Khashoggi]].<ref>{{cite web |title=White House Digs Itself in Deeper on Khashoggi |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/12/04/white-house-digs-itself-in-deeper-on-khashoggi-trump-refuses-to-address-murder-journalist-saudi-arabia-anger-congress-mohammed-bin-salman-complicit-war-in-yemen-humanitarian-disaster-gina-haspel/ |work=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]] |date=December 4, 2018|first1=Michael |last1=Hirsh |first2=Robbie |last2=Gramer}}</ref> Under mounting pressure from lawmakers who wanted action against Saudi Arabia, Mattis and Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]], in a rare closed briefing of the Senate, disputed the CIA's conclusion and declared there was no direct evidence linking the Crown Prince to Khashoggi's assassination.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trump administration defends close Saudi ties as Senate moves to end US support for Yemen war |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/28/us-cabinet-members-defend-close-saudi-ties-lawmakers-unconvinced.html |publisher=CNBC |date=November 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 19, 2018, Trump announced immediate [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War|U.S. withdrawal from Syria]], over the objections of his national security advisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/20/623246756/defense-secretary-mattis-to-retire-in-february-trump-says|title=Defense Secretary Mattis To Retire In February, Trump Says, Amid Syria Tension|publisher=NPR|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> Mattis had recently said that the U.S. would remain in Syria following the defeat of ISIL to ensure they did not regroup. The next day, he submitted his resignation after failing to persuade Trump to reconsider.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/19/678150756/reports-white-house-intends-to-pull-u-s-troops-from-syria|title=White House Orders Pentagon To Pull U.S. Troops From Syria|publisher=NPR|accessdate=December 20, 2018 |quote= The troop withdrawal is a reversal of policy discussed as recently as this month by Mattis, who said that after the defeat of ISIS, U.S. forces would remain in Syria to prevent a resurgence of the terrorist group and to counteract Iran.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html|title=Jim Mattis Resigns, Rebuking Trump's Worldview|first=Helene |last=Cooper|date=December 20, 2018|accessdate=December 20, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref> His resignation letter contained language that appeared to criticize Trump's worldview\u2014praising NATO, which Trump has often derided, and the 79-nation Defeat-ISIS coalition that Trump had just decided to abandon. Mattis also affirmed the need for \"treating allies with respect and also being clear-eyed about both malign actors and strategic competitors,\" and remaining \"resolute and unambiguous\" against authoritarian states such as China and Russia. He wrote that Trump has \"the right to have a Secretary of Defense whose views are better aligned with [his] on these and other subjects.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html|title=Jim Mattis, Defense Secretary, Resigns in Rebuke of Trump\u2019s Worldview|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=December 8, 2018|accessdate=December 21, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-sad-day-for-america-washington-fears-a-trump-unchecked-by-mattis/2018/12/20/faef8da0-04ac-11e9-b6a9-0aa5c2fcc9e4_story.html|title=\u2018A sad day for America\u2019: Washington fears a Trump unchecked by Mattis|first1=Greg|last1=Jaffe|first2=Karoun|last2=Demirjian|date=December 20, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> His resignation triggered alarm among historical allies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://on.ft.com/2Cuv6tY|title= Mattis Resignation Spreads Alarm in Washington and Abroad|first=Demetri|last=Sevastopulo|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=December 23, 2018|work=Financial Times}}</ref> Mattis's letter said his resignation would be effective February 28, 2019.<ref name=nyt20181220>{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Helene |work=The New York Times |title=Jim Mattis, Marine General Turned Defense Secretary, Will Leave Pentagon in February |date=December 20, 2018 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/20/us/politics/jim-mattis-defense-secretary-trump.html}}</ref> Three days later Trump moved Mattis's departure date up to January 1, after becoming angered by the implicit criticism of Trump's worldview in the resignation letter.<ref name=\"angry\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/23/us/politics/trump-mattis.html|title=Trump, Angry Over Mattis's Rebuke, Removes Him 2 Months Early|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=23 December 2018|accessdate=23 December 2018|work =The New York Times}}</ref> On January 2, 2019, Trump criticized Mattis's performance as Secretary of Defense and said he had \"essentially fired him.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/02/us/politics/trump-mattis-defense-secretary-generals.html|title=Trump Says Mattis Resignation Was \u2018Essentially\u2019 a Firing, Escalating His New Front Against Military Critics|first=Maggie|last=Haberman|date=January 2, 2019|newspaper =New York Times |accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPost-tenure at the October 17, 2019 [[Alfred E. Smith Memorial Foundation Dinner]], keynote speaker Mattis responded to comments Trump made about him, saying, \"I\u2019m not just an overrated general, I am the greatest, the world\u2019s most overrated...I\u2019m honored to be considered that by Donald Trump, because he also called [[Meryl Streep]] an overrated actress. So I guess I\u2019m the Meryl Streep of generals, and frankly, that sounds pretty good to me. And you do have to admit that between me and Meryl, at least we've had some victories.\" He continued, \"I've earned my spurs on the battlefield...Donald Trump earned his spurs in a letter from a doctor.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nytimes.com/2019/10/18/us/mattis-trump.html |work=The New York Times |title=Mattis Mocks Trump\u2019s Bone Spurs and Love of Fast Food |first=Christine |last=Hauser |date=October 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jim-mattis-slams-donald-trump-during-speech-al-smith-dinner-2019-10-18 |work=CBS News |title=Jim Mattis fires back at President Trump for \"overrated\" insult |first=Grace |last=Segers |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n=== Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process ===\nMattis supports a [[two-state solution]] model for [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace process|Israeli\u2013Palestinian peace]]. He has said the situation in Israel is \"unsustainable\" and that [[Israeli settlement]]s harm prospects for peace and could lead to an apartheid-like situation in the [[West Bank]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/trumps-top-pentagon-pick-said-settlements-were-creating-apartheid/ |title= Trump's top Pentagon pick said settlements were creating 'apartheid' |work=Times of Israel |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122180032/http://www.timesofisrael.com/trumps-top-pentagon-pick-said-settlements-were-creating-apartheid |archive-date=November 22, 2016 |first=Eric |last=Cortellessa |date=November 20, 2016}}</ref> In particular, he has said that the perception of biased American support for Israel has made it difficult for moderate Arabs to show support for the United States. Mattis strongly supported Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] on the Middle East peace process, praising Kerry for being \"wisely focused like a laser beam\" on a two-state solution.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/ex-us-general-we-pay-a-price-for-backing-israel |title =Ex-US general: We pay a price for backing Israel |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120155623/http://www.timesofisrael.com/ex-us-general-we-pay-a-price-for-backing-israel |archive-date=November 20, 2016 |first=Lazar |last=Berman |date=July 25, 2013 |work=Times of Israel|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Iran and Middle Eastern allies ===\n[[File:SD meets with Egypt's President 170405-D-SV709-331 (33705568522).jpg|thumb|Mattis and Egyptian President [[Abdel Fattah el-Sisi]] in April 2017]]\nMattis believes [[Iran]] is the principal threat to the stability of the Middle East, ahead of [[Al-Qaeda]] and [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]]. Mattis says: \"I consider ISIS nothing more than an excuse for Iran to continue its mischief. Iran is not an enemy of ISIS. They have a lot to gain from the turmoil in the region that ISIS creates.\" Mattis sees the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran nuclear deal]] as a poor agreement, but believes there is now no way to tear it up, saying: \"We are just going to have to recognize that we have an imperfect arms control agreement. Second, that what we achieved is a nuclear pause, not a nuclear halt\". Mattis argues that inspections may fail to prevent Iran from seeking to develop nuclear weapons, but that \"[i]f nothing else at least we will have better targeting data if it comes to a fight in the future.\"<ref name=\"Washington Examiner\" /> Additionally, he criticized Obama for being \"naive\" about Iranian intentions and Congress for being \"pretty much absent\" on the nuclear deal.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shane III|first1=Leo|title=General Mattis wants Iran to be a top focus for the next president (whoever it is)|url=http://www.militarytimes.com/story/military/2016/04/22/mattis-csis-speech-iran/83397134/ |accessdate=December 2, 2016|date=April 22, 2016|work=[[Sightline Media Group|Military Times]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Defense Secretary James Mattis & Deputy Crown Price of Saudi Arabia Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud in the Pentagon in Washington, D.C., March 16, 2017 (33323866082).jpg|thumb|Mattis with [[Saudi Arabia]]'s prince [[Mohammad bin Salman Al Saud|Mohammad]] in March 2017]]\nMattis praises the friendship of regional US allies such as [[Jordan]], [[Israel]], and the [[United Arab Emirates]].<ref name=\"defense.gov1\">{{cite news|last1=Cronk|first1=Terri Moon|title=Mattis Praises America\u2019s Security Partnership With Israel\n|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1159485/mattis-praises-americas-security-partnership-with-israel/ |accessdate=August 19, 2018|date=April 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"defense.gov2\">{{cite news|last1=Cronk|first1=Terri Moon|title=Mattis, Israeli Counterpart Discuss Mutual Security Concerns|url=https://www.defense.gov/News/Article/Article/1504866/mattis-israeli-counterpart-discuss-mutual-security-concerns/\n|accessdate=August 19, 2018|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"military.com\">{{cite news|last1=Seck|first1=Hope Hodge|title=Mattis: 'I Don't Understand' Speculation about Presidential Run|url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2016/04/22/mattis-i-dont-understand-speculation-about-presidential-run.html|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=military.com|date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> He also criticized Obama for seeing allies as \"free-loading\", saying: \"For a sitting U.S. President to see our allies as freeloaders is nuts.\"<ref name=\"military.com\" /> He has cited the importance of the United Arab Emirates and Jordan as countries that wanted to help, for example, in filling in the gaps in Afghanistan. He criticized Obama's defense strategy as giving \"the perception we're pulling back\" from US allies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grady|first1=John|title=Mattis: U.S. Suffering 'Strategic Atrophy'|url=https://news.usni.org/2015/05/14/mattis-u-s-suffering-strategic-atrophy|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=USNI News|publisher=U.S. Naval Institute|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> He stresses the need for the US to bolster its ties with allied intelligence agencies, particularly those of Jordan, [[Egypt]] and [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mu\u00f1oz|first1=Carlo|title=James Mattis, retired Marine general, says Iran nuclear deal 'fell short'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/apr/22/james-mattis-retired-marine-general-says-iran-nucl/|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=The Washington Times|date=April 22, 2016}}</ref> In 2012 Mattis argued for providing weapons to [[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War|Syrian rebels]] as a way to fight back against [[Iranian involvement in the Syrian Civil War|Iranian proxies in Syria]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ackerman|first1=Spencer|title=Military's Mideast Chief Sounds Ready to Aid Syria's Rebels|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/03/mattis-syria|accessdate=December 2, 2016|work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=March 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe departure of several of Mattis's senior deputies in the fall of 2018 caused concern in foreign policy circles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/10/31/pentagon-nato-policy-chief-steps-down-dod-defense-mattis/|title=Three Senior Pentagon Officials Leave in Quick Succession|first=Lara Seligman, Robbie|last=Gramer|publisher=|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> Many senior officials served only because of Mattis and fought political battles with the White House regularly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/15/us/politics/jim-mattis-trump-defense-relationship.html|title=Fraying Ties With Trump Put Jim Mattis\u2019s Fate in Doubt|first=Helene|last=Cooper|date=September 15, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=December 20, 2018}}</ref> One of the most serious areas of concern has been the potential for war with Iran because of the Trump Administration's withdrawal from the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|JCPOA]] at the same time the U.S. military is redeploying forces from the Middle East to the Pacific to better compete with China and contain North Korea.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 3, 2018 |accessdate=December 28, 2018|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/military-officials-alarmed-about-shrinking-military-footprint-in-middle-east-as-administration-pressures-iran/2018/11/03/44e599f4-b152-4fdc-938e-744fa5e3d6fe_story.html |title=Citing Iran, military officials are alarmed by shrinking U.S. footprint in Middle East|work=Washington Post }}</ref> Mattis opposed the withdrawal from the JCPOA, calling the deal \"the best we could come up with\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mattis-iran-is-the-biggest-threat-to-mideast-peace|title=Mattis: Iran is the biggest threat to Mideast peace|date=April 22, 2016|website=Washington Examiner}}</ref>\n\nDuring an interview on C-SPAN, the Deputy for Middle East [[Mick Mulroy]] said that Mattis focused on five distinct threats posed by Iran. The first was obtaining a nuclear weapon. The second was to maritime security in the [[Strait of Hormuz]] and the [[Bab al-Mandab]], because a substantial portion of energy trade and commercial goods go through those areas. The third was their support to proxies and terrorist organizations, including [[Hezbollah]] in Lebanon and Syria, [[Houthis]] in Yemen, some [[Hashd al-Shaabi]] in Iraq and safe-harboring senior [[al-Qaeda]] leaders in Iran. The fourth was Iranian ballistic missiles in Houthi-controlled areas of Yemen for use against Saudi Arabia and in Syria with Hezbollah to use against Israel. Cyber was the fifth threat and a growing concern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?460180-2/syria-middle-east-security-michael-mulroy-remarks|title=Syria and Middle East Security, Michael Mulroy Remarks &#124; C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org}}</ref>\n\n=== Japan ===\nMattis visited [[Japan]] one week after being sworn in as Secretary of Defense. During a meeting with [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] [[Shinz\u014d Abe]], Mattis emphasized that the U.S. remains [[Treaty of Mutual Cooperation and Security Between the United States and Japan|committed to the mutual defense of Japan]] and stated, \"I want there to be no misunderstanding during the transition in Washington that we stand firmly, 100 percent, shoulder to shoulder with you and the Japanese people.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Michael R.|last2=Rich|first2=Motoko|title=James Mattis Says U.S. Is 'Shoulder to Shoulder' With Japan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/03/world/asia/us-japan-mattis-abe-defense.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> He also reassured Japan that the U.S. would defend the disputed [[Senkaku Islands dispute|Senkaku Islands]] controlled by Japan but also claimed by China and [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/china-usa-japan-senkaku-islands-dispute-stability-security-region-james-mattis-donald-trump-a7562491.html |title=China accuses US of putting regional stability at risk over backing of Japan in island dispute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926143120/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/china-usa-japan-senkaku-islands-dispute-stability-security-region-james-mattis-donald-trump-a7562491.html |archive-date=September 26, 2017 |work=The Independent |date=February 4, 2017|first=Rebecca |last=Flood}}</ref>\n\n=== Russia ===\nSpeaking at a conference sponsored by [[The Heritage Foundation]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] in 2015, Mattis said he believed that [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]]'s intent is \"to break NATO apart.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters|url=http://www.unian.info/world/1632767-general-stating-russian-aggression-in-ukraine-much-more-severe-than-ustreats-it-may-become-defense-secretary.html |title=General stating Russian aggression in Ukraine \"much more severe\" than U.S. treats it may become Defense Secretary |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206030025/http://www.unian.info/world/1632767-general-stating-russian-aggression-in-ukraine-much-more-severe-than-ustreats-it-may-become-defense-secretary.html |archive-date=December 6, 2016 |publisher=[[UNIAN]] |date=November 19, 2016}}</ref> Mattis has also spoken out against what he perceives as Russia's expansionist or bellicose policies in [[Russian military intervention in Syria|Syria]], [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Ukraine]] and the [[Baltic states]].<ref>{{cite news |url-status=live|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/us/politics/james-mattis-secrtary-of-defense-trump.html |title=James Mattis, Outspoken Retired Marine, Is Trump's Choice as Defense Secretary |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301210650/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/01/us/politics/james-mattis-secrtary-of-defense-trump.html |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |work=New York Times |date=December 1, 2016 |first1=Michael R. |last =Gordon |first2=Eric |last2=Schmitt}}</ref> In 2017 Mattis said that the world order is \"under biggest attacks since World War Two, from Russia, terrorist groups, and China's actions in the [[South China Sea]].\"<ref name=\"Press TV\" />\n\nOn February 16, 2017, Mattis said the United States was not currently prepared to collaborate with Russia on military matters, including future anti-[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] U.S. operations.<ref name=\"baldor\" /> In August 2017, he said: \"Despite Russia's denials, we know they are seeking to redraw international borders by force, undermining the sovereign and free nations of Europe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/russia-lies-about-not-wanting-redraw-map-europe-force-mattis-tells-ukraine-655034|title=James Mattis says Russia wants to use violence to redraw the borders of Europe|date=August 25, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2018 resignation letter, Mattis called both Russia and China \"authoritarian models\" rivaling U.S. interests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-46644841|title=James Mattis' resignation letter in full|date=December 21, 2018|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretaries Tillerson and Mattis Host the U.S.-China Diplomatic and Security Dialogue With Chinese State Councilor Yang and General Fang in Washington (34604966264).jpg|thumb|Mattis and Tillerson with Chinese General [[Fang Fenghui]] and State Councilor [[Yang Jiechi]], June 2017]]\n\n=== China ===\nMattis called for [[freedom of navigation]] in the South China Sea and criticized China's [[Great Wall of Sand|island-building]] activities, saying: \"The bottom line is [...] the international waters are international waters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Katie|title=Chinese state media slams Tillerson over South China Sea|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/01/13/politics/us-tillerson-china-reaction/|accessdate=February 8, 2017|publisher=CNN Politics|date=January 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate change ===\n{{See also|Climate security}}\nIn 2017, Mattis said that budget cuts would hamper the ability to monitor the [[effects of global warming]],<ref name=\"Union of Concerned Scientists\" /> and noted, \"climate change is a challenge that requires a broader, whole-of-government response.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/james-mattis-us-defence-secretary-climate-change-destabilise-world-security-donald-trump-global-a7630676.html|title=US Defence Secretary James Mattis says climate change is already destabilising the world |year=2017 |work=The Independent}}</ref> He also told senators \"climate change is impacting stability in areas of the world where our troops are operating today.\"<ref>Ness, Erik \"The Cost of Skepticism,\" ''Brown Alumni Monthly,'' March/April 2018, p.16</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMattis has never been married<ref name=WSJ_Cooper /> and has no children.<ref name=Kovach /> He proposed to a woman, but she called off the wedding days before it was to occur, not wanting to burden his career.<ref name=\"NYBIO\" /> He is nicknamed \"The Warrior Monk\" because of his bachelorhood and lifelong devotion to the study of war.<ref name=Ollie>{{cite news|author=[[Oliver North|North, Oliver]] |title=Gen. Mattis: The Warrior Monk |url=http://insider.foxnews.com/2010/07/09/gen-mattis-the-warrior-monk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118093128/http://insider.foxnews.com/2010/07/09/gen-mattis-the-warrior-monk |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 3, 2015 |work=Fox News Insider |date=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> An avid reader, he has 7000 books in his private library,<ref>[[Bob Woodward]], ''[[Fear: Trump in the White House]]'', Simon and Schuster, 2019, p. 50</ref> and has recommended [[Marcus Aurelius]]'s ''[[Meditations]]'' as the one book every American should read.<ref>Paul Szoldra (26 September 2018), [https://www.businessinsider.com/mattis-says-every-american-should-read-this-one-book-2018-9?IR=T \"Mattis says every American should read this one book\"], ''Business Insider''. Retrieved 24 March 2020.</ref>\n\nMattis is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], and has been described as \"devout\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-john-kelly-trump-gets-a-plain-spoken-disciplinarian-as-his-chief-of-staff/2017/07/28/0c29cfc2-73db-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|title=In John Kelly, Trump gets a plain-spoken disciplinarian as his chief of staff|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|date=July 28, 2017|work=The Washington Post|access-date=June 16, 2018|last2=deGrandpre|first2=Andrew|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612234108/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-john-kelly-trump-gets-a-plain-spoken-disciplinarian-as-his-chief-of-staff/2017/07/28/0c29cfc2-73db-11e7-9eac-d56bd5568db8_story.html|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and \"committed.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/trumps-catholic-warriors|title=Trump\u2019s Catholic Warriors|work=National Catholic Register|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015449/http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/trumps-catholic-warriors|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 Iraq invasion]], he often prayed with general [[John F. Kelly]] on Sundays.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Trump transition team's formal biography of Mattis described him as \"the living embodiment of the Marine Corps motto, ''[[Semper fidelis|Semper Fidelis]]''.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> He has declined when asked by reporters to discuss his faith in public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/12/04/mattis-shows-how-to-handle-a-reporters-question-about-his-religious-beliefs/|title=Mattis Shows How to Handle a Reporter\u2019s Question About His Religious Beliefs|website=Foreign Policy|quote=That's something I stay pretty private about.| access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015603/https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/12/04/mattis-shows-how-to-handle-a-reporters-question-about-his-religious-beliefs/|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2003 PBS interview, Mattis recalled how his Marines followed advice from his chaplain on gaining the support of Iraqi citizens: \"On the suggestion of my Catholic chaplain the Marines would take chilled drinking water in bottles and walk out amongst the protesters and hand it out. It is just hard to throw a rock at somebody who has given you a cold drink of water and it's 120 degrees outside.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Military awards ==\nMattis's decorations, awards, and badges include, among others:\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}&nbsp;[[File:Navy Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]&nbsp;[[File:US Defense Superior Service Medal ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]][[File:Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|other_device=nv|ribbon=Bronze Star ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=award-star|ribbon=Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Achievement ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Combat Action Ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Navy Presidential Unit Citation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award-3d.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:U.S. Navy Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Navy Meritorious Unit Commendation ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|[[File:Marine Corps Expeditionary ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Southwest Asia Service Medal ribbon (1991-2016).svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Afghanistan Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Humanitarian Service ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=6|type=service-star|other_device=bss|ribbon=Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Marine Corps Recruiting Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:POL Z\u0142oty Medal Wojska Polskiego BAR.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=NATO Meritorious Service Medal bar.svg|width=106}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar.svg|width=106}}\n|[[File:MSC ribbon-military.png|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Kuwait Liberation Medal (Saudi Arabia) ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|[[File:Kuwait Liberation Medal (Kuwait) ribbon.svg|ribbon|106px]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:USMC Rifle Expert badge.png|150px]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:USMC Pistol Expert badge.png|150px]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[File:Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge.png|150px]]\n|}\n</center>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!1st row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] w/ one [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Legion of Merit]]\n|-\n!2nd row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Bronze Star Medal]] w/ [[Combat \"V\"]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ two [[5/16 inch star|{{frac|5|16}}\" Gold Star]]s\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]\n|-\n!3rd row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy and Marine Corps Presidential Unit Citation]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Navy Unit Commendation]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Unit Commendation|Navy and Marine Corps Meritorious Unit Commendation]]\n|-\n!4th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marine Corps Expeditionary Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[National Defense Service Medal]] w/ two [[service star|{{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Southwest Asia Service Medal]] w/ two {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|-\n!5th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n|-\n!6th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Sea Service Ribbon]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" silver star and two {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze stars\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Recruiting Service Ribbon#United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps Recruiting Service Ribbon]] w/ one {{frac|3|16}}\" bronze star\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Polish Army Medal]] in gold\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[NATO Medal|NATO Meritorious Service Medal]]<ref name=\"NATOawards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.act.nato.int/french-general-assumes-command-of-allied-command-transformation|title=French general assumes command of Allied Command Transformation|date=September 18, 2009|work=Allied Command Transformation Public Affairs Office|publisher=[[NATO]]|accessdate=September 28, 2009|location={{USS|George Washington|CVN-73}}|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006090257/http://www.act.nato.int/french-general-assumes-command-of-allied-command-transformation|archive-date=October 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n!7th row\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[NATO Medal]] for Service with ISAF<ref name=\"NATOawards\" />\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"Text-align:center\"|[[Meritorious Service Cross]] from Canada in 2013 <ref>http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2013/2013-04-27/html/gh-rg-eng.html#c101</ref>\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Kuwait Liberation Medal (Saudi Arabia)]]\n|colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Kuwait Liberation Medal (Kuwait)]]\n|-\n!Badges\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Rifle Expert Badge]] (4th award)\n|colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Marksmanship Badge (United States)|Pistol Expert Badge]] (2nd award)\n|-\n!Badge\n|colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Office of the Secretary of Defense Identification Badge]]\n|}\n</center>\n\nHis citation for the Canadian [[Meritorious Service Cross]] reads as follows: \"While occupying key leadership positions within the United States Armed Forces and NATO between 2001 and 2012, General Mattis directly and repeatedly contributed to the Canadian Forces\u2019 operational success in Afghanistan. Providing unprecedented access and championing Canadian participation in critical policy and training events, he helped shape Canadian counter-insurgency doctrine. Demonstrating unequivocal support and unwavering commitment to Canada, General Mattis has significantly strengthened Canadian-American relations and has been a critical enabler in both countries\u2019 shared achievements in Afghanistan.\"<ref>http://canadagazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2013/2013-04-27/html/gh-rg-eng.html#c101</ref>\n\n== Civilian awards ==\n[[File:Defense.gov photo essay 100428-N-0696M-076.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Mattis receiving the Distinguished Military Leadership Award from [[Michael Mullen]] at the annual Atlantic Council Awards Gala in Washington, D.C.]]\n\nMattis's civilian awards include:\n\n* 2009: [[Center for National Policy]]'s [[Center for National Policy#Edmund S. Muskie Distinguished Public Service Award|Edmund S. Muskie Distinguished Public Service Award]]<ref name=SenateNom />\n* 2010: [[Atlantic Council]]'s Distinguished Military Leadership Award<ref name=SenateNom />\n* 2013: World Affairs Council of Greater Hampton Roads \"[[Ryan Crocker|Ryan C. Crocker]] Global Citizen of the Year\" Award<ref name=FWA />\n* 2014: Marine Corps University Foundation Semper Fidelis Award<ref name=FWA />\n* 2014: [[Washington College]] honorary [[Doctor of Law#United States|doctor of laws]] degree<ref>{{cite web|title=Convocation Will Honor Marine General James Mattis|url=https://www.washcoll.edu/live/news/5053-convocation-will-honor-marine-general-james-mattis|publisher=Washington College|accessdate=June 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016: [[Washington Policy Center]] Champion of Freedom Award recipient<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpolicy.org/publications/detail/wpcs-2016-champion-of-freedom-named-secretary-of-defense|title=WPC's 2016 'Champion of Freedom' named Secretary of Defense|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Washington Policy Center|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n* Mattis is the primary subject of [[Guy Snodgrass]]'s 2019 book ''Holding the Line: Inside Trump's Pentagon with Secretary Mattis''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Holding-Line-Inside-Pentagon-Secretary/dp/0593084373|title=Holding the Line: Inside Trump's Pentagon with Secretary Mattis|last=|first=|date=|website=www.amazon.com|access-date=2019-10-21}}</ref>\n*[[Robert John Burke]] portrays Mattis in the 2008 HBO miniseries [[Generation Kill (miniseries)|''Generation Kill'']], which depicts the 2003 invasion of Iraq.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/generation-kill/cast-and-crew/maj-gen-james-mattis/index.html|title=Maj. Gen. James 'Maddog' Mattis|website=HBO}}</ref>\n* Mattis is also known for the [[Internet meme]] depicting him as \"Saint Mattis of Quantico, Patron Saint of Chaos\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Szoldra|first1=Paul|title=The Facebook page for Marine Special Ops posted a picture of 'Mad Dog' Mattis as a saint|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/marsoc-facebook-mattis-saint-2016-12|accessdate=January 25, 2017|work=Business Insider|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n* Mattis is commonly \"reported on\" by the military [[satire]] website ''[[Duffel Blog]]'' for potentially being fired,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2018/09/mattis-says-hes-absolutely-not-leaving-pentagon-while-carrying-cardboard-box-out-to-his-car/|title=Mattis says he\u2019s \u2018absolutely not\u2019 leaving Pentagon while carrying cardboard box out to his car|first=Paul|last=Sharpe|date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> winning an \"arms race\" with Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2017/03/winning-arms-race-says-mattis-workout-kremlin-gym/|title=\u2018We\u2019re winning this arms race,\u2019 Mattis says during workout at Kremlin gym|first=Cat|last=Astronaut|date=March 2, 2017}}</ref> and crossing the Potomac to launch a Roman-style ''[[coup d'\u00e9tat]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.duffelblog.com/2013/12/general-mattis-crosses-potomac-100000-troops-president-senate-flee-city/|title=General Mattis Crosses Potomac With 100,000 Troops; President, Senate Flee City|last=Scuttlebutt|first=Dick|date=December 24, 2013|website=Duffel Blog|language=en-US|access-date=December 23, 2018}}</ref>\n*Mattis is an avid reader and releases his [https://mattisbooks.com/ reading lists].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/13/defense-secretary-james-mattis-extraordinary-reading-habits.html|title=The extraordinary reading habits of Defense Secretary James Mattis|last=Macias|first=Amanda|date=2018-09-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of United States Marine Corps four-star generals]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Marine Corps}}\n* Reynolds, Nicholas E. (2005). ''Basrah, Baghdad and Beyond: The U.S. Marine Corps in the Second Iraq War''. p.&nbsp;5. Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|1-59114-717-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links |commons=Category:James N. Mattis|q=James Mattis|d=Q267902|b=no|n=no|s=Author:James N. Mattis|v=no|wikt=no}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171011204823/http://www.quotes.euronews.com/people/james-mattis-nxa8qYBW Quotes from James Mattis on ''All Views by Quotes'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z_xCQ40FOto James Mattis Sworn in As US Secretary of Defense]\n* [https://www.defense.gov/About-DoD/Biographies/Biography-View/Article/1055835/james-mattis Department of Defense biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110430125117/https://slsp.manpower.usmc.mil/gosa/biographies/rptBiography.asp?PERSON_ID=121&PERSON_TYPE=General Official Marine Corps biography]\n* {{cite news|date=June 2017 |url=http://mihsislander.org/2017/06/full-transcript-james-mattis-interview/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916053803/http://mihsislander.org/2017/06/full-transcript-james-mattis-interview/ |url