endent    =\n| trustee           =\n| specialist        =\n| MOE               =\n| ofsted            =\n| ceeb              = 211030\n| chairperson       =\n| administrator     =\n| rector            =\n| director          =\n| principal         = John Marinacci\n| head              =\n| chaplain          = Joseph Michini, [[Society of Jesus|S.J.]]\n| staff             =\n| faculty           = 150\n| teaching_staff    =\n| grades            = [[Sixth grade|6]]\u2013[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n| gender            = [[Single-sex education|Male]]\n| grade6            =\n| grade7            =\n| grade8            =\n| grade9            =\n| grade10           =\n| grade11           =\n| grade12           =\n| other             =\n| other_grade_label =\n| avg_class_size    =18\n| ratio             =\n| system            =\n| slogan            = \"Roll,Dons Roll\"\n| song              = Loyola Alma Mater\n| fightsong         = \"Come On You Dons to the Fight\"\n| athletics         =\n| conference        = [[Maryland Interscholastic Athletic Association|MIAA]]\n| sports            = Lacrosse, soccer, football, wrestling, water polo, swimming, squash, tennis, ice-hockey, basketball, volleyball, cross-country, indoor track, track & field, golf, rugby, baseball \n| mascot            = Loyola Dons\n| nickname          = Dons\n| team_name         =\n| rival             = [[Calvert Hall College High School|Calvert Hall]]\n| accreditation     = [[Association of Independent Maryland and DC Schools|AIMS]]\n| ranking           =\n| national_ranking  =\n| SAT               =1050\n| ACT               =28\n| publication       = The Blakefield Magazine\n| newspaper         = ''The Loyolan''\n| yearbook          = The Loyola\n| fees              =\n| communities       =\n| alumni            =\n| nobel_laureates   =\n| footnotes         =\n| imagesize         = 250px\n| schoolnumber      =\n| affiliation       = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Baltimore|Archdiocese of Baltimore]]<br>[[Jesuit Secondary Education Association|JSEA]]\n| president         = Anthony Day\n| head of school    =\n| headteacher       =\n| head_label        =\n| custodian         =\n| roll              =\n| school code       =\n| testaverage       =\n| testname          =\n| tuition           = $20,500\n| endowment         = $25,000,000\n| campus            =\n| campus size       = 60 acres\n| campus type       = suburban\n| mascot image      =\n| colors            = [[Blue]] and [[Gold (color)|Gold]] {{color box|blue}}{{color box|gold}}\n| enrollment        = 1,000\n| enrollment_as_of  = \n| feeders           =\n| free_label        =\n| free_text         =\n| free_label1       = Dean of Students\n| free_text1        = Bob Schlichtig\n| free_label3       = Athletic Director\n| free_text3        = Brant Hall\n| free_label5       =\n| free_text5        =\n| picture           = [[File:Loyola wheeler lawn2.jpg|280px]]\n| homepage          = [http://www.loyolablakefield.org loyolablakefield]\n}}\n'''Loyola Blakefield''', formerly '''Loyola High School''', is an American [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]], college preparatory school for boys established by the [[Society of Jesus]]. It is located in [[Towson, Maryland|Towson]], [[Maryland]], within the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Baltimore|Archdiocese of Baltimore]]. Students from [[Baltimore]], [[Baltimore County, Maryland|Baltimore County]], [[Harford County, Maryland|Harford County]], [[Carroll County, Maryland|Carroll County]], [[Howard County, Maryland|Howard County]], [[Anne Arundel County, Maryland|Anne Arundel County]], and Southern [[Pennsylvania]] attend the school. It enrolls over nine hundred students in grades six through twelve.\n\n== History ==\nArchbishop [[Francis Kenrick]] asked the Jesuits to oversee the formation of a school for laymen that would incorporate the Jesuit standards of excellence and build new men conscious of a religious purpose. His request was prompted by the 1852 closure of nearby St. Mary's College.  Construction of Loyola High School began on Charles Street in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]], in early 1852, and on September 15, 1852, the school enrolled its first students.\n\nIn the early 1930s the growing and cramped high school began to look toward moving north of the city. In 1933, with the support of the Blake family, Loyola purchased the land known today as Blakefield in [[Towson, Maryland]]. In 1941, the students moved to the new campus. Between 1981 and 1988, a Middle School was gradually introduced, and in recognition of the two levels of education, Loyola High School officially became known as Loyola Blakefield.\n\nPhysical improvements in recent years have included the construction of Knott Hall which houses the student commons and dining hall, athletic center, and alumni areas, Burk Hall academic wing, renovations to the 60-year-old science laboratories, and construction of an additional section to Wheeler Hall.\n\nLoyola Blakefield has a tradition of honoring alumni from 50 years earlier at its graduation ceremony. \"Bring back the men from 50 years before to see a new generation graduate,\" writes James Maliszewski, whose grandfather died a year before they could have attended together as 1937 and 1987 graduates.<ref name=\"50year\">{{cite web|url=http://maliszew.livejournal.com/11166.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140709095730/http://maliszew.livejournal.com/11166.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 9, 2014 |date=May 11, 2002 |title=May. 11th, 2002 journal entry |accessdate=July 6, 2014 |author=James Maliszewski }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nLoyola Blakefield competes in the [[Maryland Interscholastic Athletic Association]] (MIAA) for all interscholastic sports except for football where they are independent; in addition to the MIAA, the basketball team is also a member of the [[Baltimore Catholic League]].\n\nThe Loyola Blakefield football team also plays every [[Thanksgiving|Thanksgiving Day]] in one of the [[List of high school football rivalries (less than 100 years old)|oldest continual national Catholic high school football rivalries]], against cross-town rival [[Calvert Hall College]]. The game, known as the [[American football on Thanksgiving|Turkey Bowl]], is held at [[M&T Bank Stadium]] in Baltimore and broadcast on television and radio by [[WMAR-TV]].\n\nThe Loyola [[lacrosse]] program is among its most successful.{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}} It won eight championships in the 1980s and also won championships in 2001, 2007, 2008, and 2013. In 2007, they defeated [[Boys' Latin School of Maryland|Boys' Latin]] 10-6 in the MIAA championship game. In 2008, they defeated previously undefeated [[Gilman School|Gilman]] 12-11 in the championship game at [[Towson University]]'s Johnny Unitas Stadium before over 8,000 spectators.{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}} Loyola has produced numerous players who have continued on to play collegiate lacrosse,{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}} including National Lacrosse Hall of Famer John Stewart, and Peter Kimmel.\n\nLoyola's swimming and diving team has also achieved remarkable successes, having recorded a record run of 20 [[Maryland Interscholastic Athletic Association]] state titles in 21 years and six National Catholic Swimming Championships crowns, whilst consistently being ranked within the National Interscholastic Swim Coaches Association national Top-25 Poll for best high school swimming teams.<ref>https://support.loyolablakefield.org/swimming</ref>\n\nThe soccer program won the Maryland Championship in 2001, 2012, and 2014 and has produced Division I talent. Coach [[Lee Tschantret]], a former longtime player in the [[Major Indoor Soccer League II|Major Indoor Soccer League]], won several championships with the [[Baltimore Blast (current)|Baltimore Blast]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\nThe Loyola basketball program reached regional prominence in the 1970s when it was led by head coach Jerry Savage, who won over 600 games from 1969 to 2003.  He produced several Division I players.  Savage also coached the 1997 MIAA Championship team, the last championship of any sort for the Dons basketball program. Loyola has been in the most Baltimore Catholic League finals with 13 total and 6 championships. More recently, the program had several disappointing seasons and experienced a four-year period with four different head coaches.  Since then Josh Davalli, an All-Metro player at Cardinal Gibbons in the mid-90's, served as varsity head coach while also teaching in the Middle School.\n\nThe Loyola [[Cross country running|Cross country]] program has had much success, being the first and only team in the MIAA to complete the \"[[Three-peat]]\", then continuing to win six consecutive individual and team titles at the Maryland Interscholastic Athletic Association championship meet. Under the coaching of Jose Albornoz, the Dons have won 14 MIAA/MSA championships to bring the program's total championships to 15 since its inception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loyolablakefield.org/page/team-detail?fromId=208019&Team=212101&SeasonLabel=2016+-+2017|title=Loyola Blakefield {{!}} Team Detail|website=www.loyolablakefield.org|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> \n\nLoyola was MIAA champions in rugby for three consecutive years from 2008 to 2010, and also in 2013 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaasports.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=102&Itemid=55|title=Past MIAA Varsity Rugby Champions|publisher=Miaasports.net|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{alumni|date=January 2019}}\n===Journalism and entertainment===\n* [[Tom Clancy]], author\n* [[Jerry Kammer]], Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist\n* Tom Callahan, former senior writer for ''[[Time magazine]]'' and columnist for ''[[The Washington Post]]''. \n* [[Nathaniel Fick]], former USMC captain and author of [[One Bullet Away: The Making of a Marine Officer]]\n* [[Brendan Hines]], actor in Fox's [[Lie to Me]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2009-03-08/entertainment/0903060077_1_mentalist-cop-drama-new-american/2|title=Here's the truth: The new American TV villain is the liar|work=Baltimore Sun|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Aaron LaCrate]], music producer and fashion designer\n* [[Thomas F. Monteleone]], author\n\n===Catholicism===\n* [[George Coyne]], astronomer and Director of the [[Vatican Observatory]]\n* [[James Stafford|James Cardinal Stafford]], [[Apostolic Penitentiary]], former [[Pontifical Council for the Laity|President of the Pontifical Council for the Laity]] and former [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archbishop of Denver]]\n\n===Athletes and athletics===\n* [[Jason La Canfora]], [[NFL Network]] analyst\n* [[Akira Fitzgerald]], [[North American Soccer League]] player\n* [[Terence Garvin]], former [[National Football League]] player for the [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n* [[Mike Lookingland]], [[Baltimore Blast]] soccer player\n* [[Bruce McGonnigal]], former National Football League player\n* [[Jim McKay]], Emmy-winning Olympic sports caster and host of the ''[[Wide World of Sports (U.S. TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''\n* [[Bob Williams (quarterback)|Bob Williams]], former National Football League player\n* [[Bill Stromberg]], [[College Football Hall of Fame]] wide receiver and [[CEO]] of [[T. Rowe Price]]\n* [[Steele Stanwick]], [[University of Virginia]] lacrosse player, recipient of the [[Tewaaraton Award]]\n\n===Marylandia===\n* [[Ephraim Francis Baldwin]], architect for [[B&O Railroad]]\n* [[J. Joseph Curran, Jr.]], former [[Attorney General of Maryland]]\n* [[Thomas L. J. D'Alesandro III]], former Mayor of [[Baltimore]] and brother of [[Nancy Pelosi]], Minority Leader of the [[United States House of Representatives]]\n* Bill Henry, member of the [[Baltimore City Council]]\n* [[Carl Stokes (Baltimore)|Carl Stokes]], member of the [[Baltimore City Council]]\n* [[James T. Smith Jr.]], [[Maryland]] Secretary of Transportation\n\n===Science and technology===\n* [[George L. Drusano]], physician and medical researcher\n* [[Bradley M. Kuhn]], computer scientist and [[free software]] activist\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Jesuit secondary schools in the United States]]\n*[[Loyola University Maryland]]\n*[[National Catholic Educational Association]]\n*[[Parochial school]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.jsea.org Jesuit Secondary Education Association]\n*[http://www.loyolablakefield.org/ Loyola Blakefield Homepage]\n*[http://www.archbalt.org/ Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Baltimore]\n\n{{Portalbar|Baltimore|Maryland|Schools|Catholicism}}\n{{Baltimore County, Maryland Schools}}\n{{Jesuit Secondary Education Association}}\n{{RC Archdiocese of Baltimore}}\n{{Maryland Private Schools}}\n{{Boys' schools in Maryland}}\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Catholic secondary schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1852]]\n[[Category:Jesuit high schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Private schools in Baltimore County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Baltimore County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:1852 establishments in Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loyola_Blakefield"}
